Republican strategy to resist Obama 's reelection
Republican leaders justified their policies by the need to combat election fraud.
However, the Brennan Center considers the latter a myth, claiming that election fraud is rarer than death by lightning in the United States.
And Republican lawyers counted only 300 cases of voter fraud in the United States in a decade.
One thing is certain: these new trends will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions partly discredit the American system of democracy.
Unlike Canada, the states are responsible for the organization of federal elections in the United States.
That's why most state governments since 2009 have passed laws that make it harder to register or vote.
This phenomenon gained new momentum after the November 2010 elections, which brought the Republicans 675 new seats in 26 states.
As a result, in 2011 alone, 180 bills were passed that restricted voting rights in 41 states.
New election laws require that voters present photo ID and proof of U.S. citizenship.
In addition, these laws reduce early voting, abolish the right to register to vote on election day, and deprive citizens with a criminal record of the right to vote.
Before the 2006 election, no state in the United States required voters to show a photo ID.
Indiana was the first state to introduce such a requirement.
The U.S. Supreme Court upheld the constitutionality of an Indiana law in 2008.
Republican officials quickly expanded the practice to other states.
In the last two years, they've initiated bills requiring voters to show photo ID in 34 states.
It is important to note that unlike in Quebec, U.S. citizens do not have a universal identity document such as a health insurance card.
In fact, 11% of American citizens, or 21 million people of voting age, do not have a photo ID issued by their state government.
And five million new voters in 2012 don't have one.
The cost of obtaining the required identity card often exceeds a hundred dollars.
The new restrictions disproportionately affect young people, minorities and people with low incomes.
In fact, 25 percent of African-Americans, 15 percent of people earning less than $35,000, 18 percent of people over the age of 65, and 20 percent of voters between the ages of 18 and 29 do not have the required photo ID.
But that's not all.
Student voters, who are believed to vote for Democratic candidates, are not permitted in several states to use photo IDs issued by their school.
But those same states allow members of fishing and hunting clubs, who vote mostly Republican, to use the voting cards issued by those clubs.
Until 2004, no state required proof of U.S. citizenship to vote.
Arizona is the first state to introduce such a requirement.
Since 2011, more than a dozen states have passed laws requiring voters to prove they are U.S. citizens.
These measures are clearly aimed at limiting the voting of Latinos.
Two-thirds of Latino voters are believed to vote for the Democratic Party.
In addition, Republican lawmakers initiated legislation in 2011 abolishing voter registration on election day in eight states.
They also restricted the ability of individuals or groups to provide assistance to those who wish to register.
This restriction was not without consequences.
For example, in the 2004 elections, a voter registration campaign helped to register some 10 million citizens.
Meanwhile, measures taken since 2009 have led to a 17% drop in the rate of registration of new voters in 2010 compared to 2006.
In addition, Republican legislators have passed laws in five other states aimed at reducing the early voting period.
For example, in the 2008 Florida general election, 33% of early voters were African American, although the latter made up only 13% of the state's total voters.
The same thing happened with the Latin Americans.
Representing only 11% of the electorate, they made up 24% of the citizens who voted early.
Unlike whites, who make up 76% of the electorate, only 46% of those who voted early voted.
Of course, Democratic lawmakers and their supporters have been active in opposing the passage of laws that restrict voter registration.
Several bills were vetoed by Democratic governors.
The most controversial laws were suspended by the intervention of the Attorney General of the United States.
This has helped to limit the negative effects.
For example, only 16 of 34 states have laws requiring photo ID.
However, the new rules that have come into effect will certainly make it difficult to exercise the right to vote in the 2012 elections.
Critics from the Democrats condemn the bias of the laws that were passed, seeing them as clearly aimed at influencing the outcome of the 2012 elections in key states.
A 2011 Brennan Center report shows that states that have passed these laws represent 171 of the 270 electoral votes needed to win the presidential election.
It is too early to say with certainty that these legislative changes at the level of the electoral system will have a significant impact on the outcome of the 2012 presidential election.
One thing is certain: these new provisions will have a negative impact on voter turnout.
In this sense, such actions are in part discrediting the American system of democracy.
