Another study, this time in Europe, found different mortality rates in those who had been screened and those who had not.
This study also showed that after 12 years of follow-up, the chances of metastasis were 30 to 40 percent higher in those who had not been screened.
So I would recommend getting tested at age 50, or at age 40 if you have a close relative who's had prostate cancer.
African-American men are also at increased risk.
The key is to make the right decision as soon as the cancer is found.
Cancers can be either aggressive or slow-moving.
