Higgs boson in detail
Last summer, the news that scientists may have discovered the Higgs boson caused quite a stir - and for good reason.
This boson is thought to account for the mass of all particles in the universe, no matter how much or how little.
It is also the last particle predicted to exist in the Standard Model - our best, or at least least least "least perfect" description of the nature and behavior of matter - but which has never been detected experimentally before.
But physicists are not yet sure that this is the Higgs boson.
We know, without a shadow of a doubt, that we are dealing with a truly new particle, and that it is very similar to the Higgs boson predicted by the Standard Model.
And new data presented this week at a major physics conference in Kyoto seems to support that, although some data is not yet available to be sure.
But let's say we're talking about the Higgs boson, because the chances of being wrong seem minimal, and let's see what that means.
There is one law in this world that is absolutely inescapable, which is that two things cannot be in the same place at the same time.
There is no way around this rule, don't even try too hard, or you will hurt yourself.
But while particle physics is a rather strange world, it turns out that it too has one law of a similar nature: the Pauli exclusion principle, which posits that two particles cannot occupy the same space at the same moment in time if they are in the same "quantum state" - that "state" is, in general, some of their characteristics.
Based on this, physicists divide particles into two categories.
In one corner, we find decent citizens, called fermions, who wisely obey the Pauli principle.
In the other, there are the bosons, a vile gang of anarchists who have no respect for anything - at least not for this principle, which means that they can be in the same place at the same time.
According to the highly unusual Particle Adventure site at Berkeley Lab, these bosons are divided into two groups: mesons, which we won't discuss here, and "force particles", which are the main forces of nature, and which the Higgs boson is a part of.
These bosons themselves, it should be emphasized, are not all as exotic creatures as one might think.
In fact, if you're able to read this history, it's because of one incredibly mundane boson: the photon, or "light particle", which is the courier of the electromagnetic force.
In fact, when a single particle with an electric charge accelerates or changes direction, it disrupts the electromagnetic field at that particular location, much like a stone thrown into a pond.
From this "breach" an electromagnetic wave (light, or infrared, or ultraviolet, etc.) is born, and this wave is nothing but a photon - and therefore one of the "force carriers" bosons.
A more stable field
The same is true for the Higgs boson, except that in order for this boson to be created, another field, the Higgs field, must be violated.
But the Higgs boson is much, much more stable than the electromagnetic field; to get it excited, you have to reach very, very high energies, as if you were talking about a frozen pond, the surface of which could only be shaken by a very large rock.
That's why you need a huge particle accelerator like the one that's operating at CERN -- the Large Hadron Collider, which is a ring that's 27 kilometers across! -- to achieve these enormous energies.
The analogy with the electromagnetic field is also useful for explaining the relationship between the Higgs boson and mass.
In fact, not all particles and not all materials interact with the electromagnetic field.
Some of them, like magnets, interact, and some of them don't interact, like a piece of paper, which will never stick to the refrigerator.
Similarly, not all particles interact with the Higgs field: those that do interact have mass, while others (like the photon, by the way) don't.
So, what does all this research "can bring", asks Mrs. Plaumondon?
In science, they are used to test the validity of the Standard Model (SM), and this also allows physicists to detect discrepancies between observational results and SM predictions.
And some of them are eager to see that discrepancy uncovered, because the slightest discrepancy can open the door to new physics and close some of the holes in the Model.
The latter, it must be said, still has significant flaws, offering no explanation for gravity (oh!) or for dark matter, which makes up about 80% of the universe (oh-oh!).
But so far, no such discrepancy has been found at CERN.
The Consequences
It's harder to predict how this research will benefit the average person's daily life, but it would be a mistake to assume it doesn't.
Look: back in the early 1960s, the pioneers of laser research at Bell Labs could not have even imagined the revolution their work would bring.
They envisioned their applications in science, but nothing more.
In fact, the late physicist Willard Boyle, who worked at Bell Labs, where the laser was invented in 1960, and who himself developed the first continuous laser (previous ones were pulsed) in 1962, said that originally the laser was seen more as a "laboratory gadget".
I mean, imagine that.
And also, an app can be found for the toolkit that accompanies the research.
For example, this same Willard Boyle, during his optical research in 1969, developed a small light sensor.
This sensor, although not its original purpose, is now the eye of all digital cameras in the world and won the 2009 Nobel Prize in Physics.
Now, this doesn't mean that the work of the Large Hadron Collider will necessarily change our lives, but it does show that anything is possible.
Palliative care is the best way to die...
The Quebec Commission for a Decent Death recently discussed the sensitive issue of end-of-life.
The debate is due to resume shortly, and a bill is being drafted.
However, much remains to be done in this vital area.
"Debt" tried to take a closer look.
Only a few weeks ago, Mr. L. was living alone in his apartment in Montereggio.
Prostate cancer, which had been destroying him from the inside, gave him a two-year reprieve.
"I was given five years, I lived seven", he says, between life and death, lying in bed in the Victor-Gadboua palliative care shelter in Belloy, where he arrived the day before.
"But it's always a shock, and you can't prepare for it", he says.
The disease does its job: incredible weakness that prevents you from going to the bathroom or even eating on your own.
Sitting at a table with a delicious meal, he gives up and agrees to be helped to eat.
He's alive, even manages to smile, to talk to strangers who work around him, bring him medicine, take him to the bathroom.
Courage in the face of a common death.
"My greatest desire is to be cured of diarrhea, which is humiliating", he admits.
A few hours later, the staff found a cure for this ailment.
"Throughout life, we are taught that a man should urinate standing up", says Pierre Broder, a psychologist at the Victor-Gadbois shelter.
To regress to the status of a child is an unbearable humiliation for some.
"It's all about the ability of people" to accept decline, he says.
Because, according to many people in palliative care, the most important events happen in the midst of this decline.
The patients who come to Victor Gadbois' hospice are all cancer patients.
The prognosis is three months to live, tops.
At this point, the team of doctors and nurses is no longer providing what is called "therapeutic" care.
Mrs. A., 89, has the greatest fear of dying "in consciousness from suffocation".
But the illness has allowed me to know my children.
"I have good children", she adds.
"I don't want anything more in my life", she says before being given permission to put on a mask to help her breathe.
She is still waiting for the last visit of her son, who has arrived from Italy.
The Victor Gadbois shelter provides care and nutrition assistance through a group of volunteers.
It's the palliative care that's left over when there's nothing more to do.
To make dying more comfortable.
In Quebec, there is one place in a palliative care facility for every 11,700 residents.
It's not much, considering we're all gonna die sooner or later.
Life here continues in the best possible conditions, explains Dr. Christian Martel, one of the hospice's doctors.
Whether it's physical, emotional or spiritual comfort.
We will agree to give the dying person mouth rinses of brandy or Pepsi, depending on what he asks for.
We don't make diabetics control their blood sugar anymore.
And death is a part of everyday life.
We brought beer last night to Mr. X, who died tonight.
His son drank that beer in the dead man's legs this morning.
"We are helping the families as well as the patients", says Natalie Savar, director of patient care.
At Victor Gadbois, no day is the same.
Alongside a 93-year-old man enjoying his last encounter with his family in the backyard, reclining on his pillows while a toast is made to him, tragically dies a young man of 36 surrounded by his parents, wife and two young children and who has tried everything to survive.
"In the last six months, three to five beds have always been occupied by cancer patients under the age of 45", says Dr. Christian Martel with concern.
53% of the patients admitted to Victor-Gadboa's shelter come from home, and 47% from the hospital.
The problem of access to palliative care
It is estimated that 77% of Canadians simply do not have access to palliative care, which is the care that is provided to alleviate the suffering of patients entering the final stages of their lives, whether at home, in a hospital or in a shelter.
And some institutions, such as the Victor Gadbois Home and the Palliative Home Care Society of Greater Montreal, specialize more or less exclusively in caring for cancer patients.
It is this gap in Quebec's health care system that is making many palliative care practitioners fearful of a bill that would legalize euthanasia and assisted suicide.
Since October, a manifesto has been circulating, signed by the luminaries of palliative care, Dr. Balfour Mount and Dr. Bernard Lyapuant, expressing their disapproval of such an initiative.
According to Dr. Christian Martel, Quebec's health care system is not efficient enough to ensure the right to high-quality palliative care before euthanasia is allowed.
She says, "I recently saw a patient who spent 14 days in the emergency room in excruciating pain, and no one took the necessary steps to help her.
I'm afraid that patients are willing to die because they don't get the proper care.
At the same time, many cancer doctors are still trying to save their patients, despite the pessimistic prognosis.
Helen Richards's chances of survival were already slim when she stopped the grueling chemotherapy.
When I told my oncologist that I was stopping treatment, she told me that she regretted that I was stopping the fight", she says.
She told me that my days were numbered!
There is no cure-all.
Dr. Martell believes that 90 percent of patients who ask for death thank the nursing staff for not granting their request after the palliative care team eases their pain.
However, it should be noted that palliative care is not an absolute panacea for pain.
According to Elsie Monroe, director of palliative care at the Home Palliative Care Society of Greater Montreal, patients are not susceptible to pain relief in 8% of cases.
At the end of life, doctors often use palliative sedation, in which the patient sleeps until the moment of death, either occasionally or permanently.
We can no longer pretend that we are unaware of this suffering.
Increasingly, patients who are unable to relieve pain will be able to access palliative sedation.
Patients in pain always say the same thing: "I want to die".
But it doesn't necessarily mean "I want to be euthanized", it means "I want to feel better".
