Pay and sell without banks - with Bitcoin
The complete opposite of current monetary exchange, based on central banks, numbered transactions between the receiving parties and the commission fees for processing them.
And then, as is so often the case with these technologies, there is obviously a political vision: the belief that the current monetary system, consisting of banking monopolies, is leading to financial crises.
In fact, Bitcoin, invented by Satoshi Nakamoto (a pseudonym), is both a virtual currency (but convertible to dollars, euros ...) and a secure exchange protocol like BitTorrent, which allows the exchange of files between participants of the same level.
About 200,000 transactions have already been logged from 15,000 computers on the network.
Several thousand sites accept bitcoins as donations or as payment.
Bitcoin peaked at $30 (€23) in June 2011, then dropped to $2 five months later, before returning to around $10 today (the rates are listed on bitcoincharts.com).
Nothing special compared to the world exchange of real money or financial products.
Nevertheless, the European Central Bank (ECB) in its report on virtual currency published in October, took an interest in this system.
He describes bitcoin as "the most successful virtual currency", "competing with the dollar or the euro" and "similar to conventional currencies".
Bitcoin differs from other types of virtual currency as "credits" used to promote a video game, which are earned in the game or which can be bought (and sometimes exchanged).
Facebook has also developed a similar system.
But the exchange is always controlled and processed by some central organ.
In Bitcoin, all nodes are simultaneously book-keepers, auditors, currency issuers, buyers and sellers.
How does this network work?
Every transaction between two users is actually between two email addresses, like an email.
Only for each new payment the user can choose a different address, thus ensuring anonymity.
The set of information pertaining to this transaction is signed electronically using a double-key encryption system.
The network can also verify the authenticity of the transaction.
Because of the contents of the file, it's possible to verify that the bitcoins used in the transaction actually exist in a public ledger sent across the network.
The key step is to register a new transaction in this ledger.
It goes through a mathematical problem sent to the computer, which, like a temporary central bank, gets the privilege of adding this new line.
It's the phase of hashing a file, which is converting a large file into a digital signature that's short and unique.
The computers take the new transaction and add a number to it before hashing it all together.
The goal is to find a number that will give a unique digital signature (many zeros at the beginning).
Once that number is found, other nodes can easily verify that it's correct.
The transaction thus becomes indissolubly linked to the chain of all other transactions; any modification will change the digital signature.
If, for the purpose of fraud, a user would very quickly (in less than ten minutes) wish to pay twice for the same money, only one of the two transactions would be confirmed by the network - and the other would remain unconfirmed, since they have different electronic signatures.
The computer that solves the problem gets 50 bitcoins.
To avoid inflation, the prize is regularly split in half, probably until the end of 2012.
The number of bitcoins in circulation is therefore limited to 21 million, but they are divisible by one hundred million, which still leaves a reserve...
The complexity of the problem also increases with the increase in computing power.
The life of the web has had its ups and downs.
Websites providing Bitcoin services were attacked, and Bitcoins were stolen from the reserves.
"The defect in use is not the protocol itself", says Pierre Nouaz, who recently launched Paymium, a company that makes payments with real money using the Bitcoin network.
The ECB also reported the possibility of money laundering through this anonymous service.
But cash also has this drawback.
