This is another risky move by President Mohamed Morsi.
With Egypt more divided than ever over the constitutional declaration that temporarily gives him extraordinary powers, he has decided to play it safe.
To everyone's surprise, he announced on Wednesday that the Constituent Assembly would vote on the final text the next day.
Exactly a week ago, the head of state gave the Assembly two additional months to finish the work.
For nearly two years, Egypt has relied on a draft text that has been amended several times, weakening institutional stability and leading to legal contradictions.
This new initiative has only further divided the country.
According to his opponents, the President persists in his "autocratic delusion", continuing to "violet the given word" and "trample the law".
In the camp of his followers, this is the way to end the institutional and political crisis, by accelerating the transition process.
The referendum must be held within fifteen days.
A very short period of time that makes the Brothers abandon their intention to explain the text to the Egyptians, article by article.
It's also a way for the president to restore public and democratic legitimacy, while discontent rages across the country.
Mohamed Morsi seems convinced that the Egyptians will vote in favor, as he stated in an interview with the American magazine Time.
Moreover, the call for an early vote is an ultimatum to the Egyptian people: "Either you vote for my text, or I reserve extraordinary powers", which are supposed to end after the adoption of the constitution.
In this strange atmosphere, 85 members of the Constituent Assembly, mostly Islamists, voted for the text yesterday.
Most liberals did not respond to the challenge.
In mid-November, just before the constitutional declaration, they slammed the door, feeling unable to make a statement.
Representatives of human rights defenders, religious minorities or civil society did the same.
To reach the necessary quorum, 11 people, reserve participants, were hastily added yesterday morning.
Some are very close to the Muslim Brotherhood.
Not surprisingly, most of the articles were voted unanimously.
Commentators were amused, by the way, by the fact that one of the few disagreements of the day was around... the time for prayer, as some committee members felt that the hours of the Constituent Assembly were set incorrectly.
The text, which was still on the ballot yesterday, contains 234 articles.
The subject of much public attention, Article 2 ultimately remained the identical article from the 1971 Constitution, stating that "the principles of Sharia are the main source of law".
Salafist parties, for whom the introduction of Islamic law is one of the main requirements, hoped to replace "principles" with "rules", which would allow for their more rigorous application.
For Islamists, the fact that this article has not been changed is a testament to their goodwill and respect for other members of Egyptian society.
"Hypocrisy", say the liberals, who see it as a PR stunt.
Because they think the Islamization of the Constitution is happening through other articles.
They pointed in particular to Article 220, which gives Al-Azhar University an advisory role, particularly in checking the compliance of laws with the Sharia.
This is alarming, according to Egypt expert Sophie Pommier, because "the people who are called upon to make decisions are not elected and have no democratic legitimacy".
We can see the emergence of a theocracy".
Many liberals are also excited by the fact that the next president of this university is likely to be much less moderate than the current one.
"There is no specific religious interference at this time.
With this constitution, we remain within the framework of civil law.
