At the meeting of the audit committee in the Chamber of Deputies, you spoke about a joint project between the Czech and German sides, in which the legislation on public procurement of both countries was compared.
What exactly was that about?
I mean, parallel testing, which we started, like, two years ago.
In short, it is about European legislation determining how public procurement should be carried out, followed by national legislation and then also the practical application.
All the information was collected and, even with the verification still incomplete, interesting differences were discovered - to put it simply, our legislation may be "accurate and infallible", but in practice we are inferior to Germany in some parameters.
It follows that it is not enough to create more and more detailed rules, we must focus on the application of the law itself.
How can this project help you, what does it mean to you?
It is this kind of joint control that can contribute to efforts to stop the refinement of laws, the reduction and improvement of restrictions, because it does not lead to a positive result.
Economics means getting the right thing for a reasonable (but not always low) price to avoid enrichment and possibly criminal behavior.
