Poland and space.
Last week, at the European Space Agency Ministerial Meeting, Poland was accepted as the 20th member of the European Space Agency, the second country from the former Eastern bloc (after the Czech Republic, which became a full member of ESA on September 12, 2008).
Poland began close cooperation with ESA in 1994 and has taken an active part in a number of the agency's projects over the years.
But Poland's journey into space began much earlier.
Even before World War II, Polish enthusiasts were engaged in spaceflight, but this was not always met with understanding.
I will remind you, for example, of the lecture by A. Sternfeld, who on December 6, 1933, presented at the Warsaw Astronomical Observatory the ideas from his groundbreaking work "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
The ideas of the young engineer (born in 1905) left the audience indifferent, after a few years, Sternfeld recalled that only Dr. Jan Gadomsky was interested in his work.
In 1934, in France, Sternfeld won the Robert Esno-Petri and André Louis Hirsch Prize for his "Introduction to Cosmonautics".
Dr. Jan Gadomski (1899-1966) was a prominent astronomer and cosmonaut who was a pioneer in the field of astronomy and cosmonautics.
He has published hundreds of articles in Polish journals and written a number of books on these scientific disciplines.
Gadomsky became a world-renowned propagandist of space science, and his contribution was recognized in part by the naming of one of the craters on the far side of the Moon in his honor.
Already in 1925 in Poland was built railway train, equipped with a rocket engine.
Unfortunately, the author of this idea remains unknown, as well as the details of the project.
It's not even clear if a missile was used to accelerate or to slow the carriage.
The only information about this drezinja is from the press of that era.
From 1933, the Polish artillery began to think about rocket arrows.
The research was carried out by the Section of Armament Technology in cooperation with professors Mechislav Wolfke and Gustav Mokzitski.
The surviving material shows that the research had reached the stage of practical testing.
But with the arrival of the German troops, the work was interrupted.
In 1937, the idea of a photoelectric fighter-rocket, proposed by engineer Rogozinsky, appeared in the specialized press, and the next year the work "Air rocket-torpedo and aviation rocket-bomb" by author Leliwy-Kzywoblotsky was published.
Both designs were developed for military use of rocket engines.
Before the war, all military projects of missile technology were handled by the Provisional Scientific Advisory Committee (Tymczasowy Komitet Doradczo-Naukowy), which coordinated all the work.
The committee was established in 1937, but after two years of its activity, the work ended due to the outbreak of war.
The next scientific work on cosmonautics appeared in the Polish press after the war, thanks to the work of the Polish Astronaut Society (Polskie Towarzystwo Astronautyczne).
The first mention of the society was in the November 1954 issue of the magazine "Problemy", which published four voluminous articles on astronautics.
In one of them, Professor M. Subotovich proposed to organize a society that would be engaged in cosmonautics.
At that time, satellite projects were gaining momentum, and it was clear that space exploration was a promising industry.
Since the beginning of 1956, the Polish Astronautical Society (POA) has been trying to join the International Federation of Astronautics (founded in 1951), and already in the autumn POA became its full member.
The following year, the first chairman of the PIA Kazimierz Zarankiewicz (1902-1959) became the deputy chairman of the International Federation of Astronautics.
He remained in this position until his death in 1959.
Since 1956, the Polish Air Force has made a significant contribution to the development of the highly successful RM (Rakieta Meteorologiczna) meteorological rocket, which became the first Polish rocket to perform scientific research.
The first type RM-1 was completed in 1957, and the first launch took place on 10 October 1958.
The missile, capable of overcoming a distance of 1800 m, was about 80 cm long, and its weight was less than 5 kg.
An improved version of the RM-1A was subsequently built, and in the summer of 1959 tests of the two-stage RM-2 rocket were conducted in the Bled Desert.
This missile was about 1.4 meters long and weighed about 11.5 kilograms.
The next version of the rocket was already capable of real scientific work - the RM-34 rocket could cover 14.5 km, and its task was to observe high-altitude winds.
But in 1962 further development was suspended.
The successor to the first RM-type missiles was the Meteor-1 missile, developed between 1962 and 1965.
The missile was conceived as a two-stage, its total length was 510 cm, and the initial weight was 32.5 kg.
Three types were developed (designated Meteor-1A, -1B and -1C), which differed in the size of the chamber for scientific equipment.
The Meteor-1A rocket had a space of 0.4 liters, the Meteor-1B had a space of 0.34 liters, and the Meteor-1C had a space of 0.62 liters.
The maximum flight range of all three types was 37 km.
Between 1965 and 1968, the Institute of Aviation developed the Meteor-2 rocket, and its first flight tests began in October 1970.
The 380 kg launch weight of the Meteor-2 rocket was capable of carrying a 10 kg payload to an altitude of about 60 km.
The Meteor-2N and Meteor-3 versions were then built.
It is also worth mentioning Poland's entry into COSPAR (Committee on Space Research) in 1960 and the creation of the national COSPAR committee two years later.
In addition, within the framework of the Intercosmos program, Poland participated in the research of space on Soviet artificial satellites, and in 1978 Polish pilot Miroslav Germashovsky became the second intercosmonaut after Vladimir Remek.
