It was a blow to the prestige of the United States, which was later compounded by an unsuccessful attempt to free the hostages by force.
The diplomats were finally released after 444 days, following negotiations mediated by the Algerian government.
Their fate has sparked a wave of solidarity and anti-Iranian sentiment at home.
Defeat in Iran was a major factor in Jimmy Carter's defeat in the 1980 presidential election, which ended with the election of Ronald Reagan.
Directed by actor Ben Affleck, Operation Argo is an episode in history that brought America small victories.
Shortly before the occupation of the embassy, six employees managed to escape.
After a difficult stint, they ended their journey at the Canadian embassy residence.
The CIA, working with the Canadian government, managed to get them out of Iran, helped by an extravagant cover story that they had left on Canadian passports as part of a film crew looking for a location in the country for a science fiction epic.
Combination of genres
The plan, devised by evacuation expert Tony Mendes, required Hollywood's cooperation.
To make the legend credible, the film was written about in the magazines, press conferences were held, and the fictional production company had a real office.
The details of the operation were kept secret for a long time, the film is based on the memoirs of Tony Mendes.
The Affleck film is a special combination of several genres.
On the one hand, a real political thriller, the so-called "movie-kinopus", the story of a successful plot, a scam - an example can be a series of films about the friends of Ocean.
The film is constantly changing moods - on the one hand, the documentary-conceived scenes from Tehran (titles show iconic historical photos of events and how the same situations were demonstrated in the film - there are no big differences).
On the other hand, the light-hearted Hollywood passages, interspersed with irony and moderate exaggeration.
And then there are scenes from CIA headquarters and other agencies, where men in suits discuss the situation at the negotiating tables, on the agency's stairs, on the phone...
Ben Affleck has done a great job of resetting his career.
The mocked actor became a respected director, and his performance was no longer the object of ridicule.
Operation Argo is his third feature film, following the dark detective Goodbye Baby Goodbye (2007) and the thriller The City (2010).
At the same time, it is Affleck's first film not to be shot in the director's hometown of Boston.
The sense of place is one of the qualities that elevated the director's earlier films above the Hollywood standard.
And Affleck shows that in Argo, where Tehran is playing Canada.
The best scenes in the film take place in the streets, in the reconstruction of real events - the opening scenes of the embassy fall are impressive with their clarity, which also conveys the emotions of confusion and unpredictability that arise when somewhere suddenly the story changes.
Afflek and his colleagues achieve a similar effect in fictional scenes (a fake headquarters in the Tehran bazaar).
Too many processes in too many places.
The director had to deal with the fact that the narrative does not involve many exciting scenes of cinematic significance.
He works quite well with these few, sometimes he makes things up - there it all comes out not so elegantly (the scene in which a phone call in America prevents an impending crisis at the Tehran airport, and the chase on the runway looks rather fanciful).
The disadvantage of Argo is the scatteriness associated with the need to show too many events in too many places.
Alan Arkin and John Goodman as Hollywood co-stars are indeed charming, but their characters deserve more space, and they're far from alone in the film.
Affleck's film lacks a bit of drama, it's a film that can be watched with moderate interest, appreciating the staging and the retro style that recreates the thrillers of the seventies.
But it's hard to catch.
But this is enough to remind us of one still somewhat alive story, and to show how the idea of omnipotent and omniscient intelligence agencies is exaggerated.
Rules of ballooning, bananas and the circus
The portal www.bankovnipoplatky.com, which annually conducts a survey on the most absurd bank charges, has now decided to announce a competition for "the most absurd regulation or project from the EU workshop".
"We were spurred to this by the latest development, in which the EU plans to adopt a 40 percent quota for women in the administration of large European companies", Patrick Nager, the organizer of the poll, told Prav.
Among the absurdities already nominated is the recent decision of the European Court to unite the rates of insurance contributions for men and women.
Until now, women have had the benefit of life insurance because insurance companies have seen them as objectively less exposed to risk.
"The next incredible ideas from the EU workshop can be put forward for competition by the end of this year.
The voting itself will take place until the end of February 2013", Nager said.
The EU's controversial regulations include, for example, the mandatory addition of bio-components to fuel, which has resulted in environmental damage, the ban on the use of reliable mercury thermometers only because they contain relatively few dangerous substances, or the directive on the size of the cage for chickens, which has resulted in a significant increase in the price of eggs this year.
The de facto ban on the use of the term "sandwich oil" or the removal of classic light bulbs from sale has also been criticized.
A good banana is about four inches long.
The pan-European apparatus often makes decisions under pressure from a trade or industrial lobby, whose positions in Brussels are usually defended by a state or group of states (thus the Czech Republic now even defends the demands of its banks under the threat of veto).
The lobby's interests are as follows: for example, the highest quality bananas in the European Union had to reach a length of 14 cm and could not show "abnormal curvature".
The European Commission's justification was that it was only harmonizing existing disparate national rules that were making trade difficult.
The EU, despite the resistance of some states, has softened standards on fruit and vegetables, citing that the existing directives will lead to waste.
Last year's EU regulation, which requires that balloons be marked with a warning that children under the age of eight cannot inflate them without adult supervision, may also be a candidate to win the poll.
The EU has turned to US studies that show that balloons are a potential cause of death by suffocation in children.
A similar restriction now applies to children under 14 years of age, who are prohibited from blowing into fairground fights.
Funny ideas are born at home too
The rule for European officials themselves is also absurd enough: anyone who holds an official position in the EU cannot use the name Macedonia, given the sensitivity of the subject for Greece, but must instead say "BYRM" (Former Yugoslav Republic of Macedonia).
Bankovnípoplatky.com, in cooperation with the liberal economists' association "The Non-Interference Principle" (Laissez Faire), has proposed for voting, in addition to the few absurd rules mentioned above, for example, the EU rule on the amount of food stocks in the territory of the member state.
The EU has set a maximum amount of food stocks that can be stored in the Czech Republic on the day of its accession to the EU.
The Czech Republic subsequently exceeded, for example, the prescribed quantities of canned mushrooms, for which it was threatened with a large fine.
The organizers of the survey were also interested in the idea of paying some countries for not having a sea, and the idea of providing subsidies for the application for subsidies.
But these ideas originated in Prague, not Brussels.
"We are at a disadvantage because we have no sea.
We will ask the European Union for compensation", said the then Minister of Agriculture Jaroslaw Palas (PSD) in the autumn of 2004.
As an argument, he pointed out that the country had a high grain harvest, and as a result of the so-called intervention procurement, the state had full warehouses of stocks that had to be taken out.
Because the Czech Republic is far from the ports, the EU, according to Palas, had to pay us hundreds of millions of euros.
As a result, the European Commission went to the Czech Republic, organizing a tender for the purchase of grain from landlocked countries.
The subsidy was offered to the villages by the Ministry for Regional Development, headed by Minister Pavel Nemts (US-DEU), in particular, such subsidies were to be used to draw up an application for subsidies from Brussels.
EU: Exceptional orders are the exception
While decisions in member states are easily criticized, the EU's efforts to regulate and to make the EU more efficient and more developed are, in the opinion of many experts, more to be commended.
The problem, according to experts, is the drawing of EU funds for projects that have nothing to do with deepening European integration, but which Member States have agreed to at budgetary level.
It is also causing emotions among the Czechs that, as in other EU countries, the Czech Republic has to fight in Brussels for the right to specific identification of its traditional products, and it does not always win this competition.
Although the Czechs after six years of fighting with the Germans and Austrians kept the name "Olomoutsky syrky", however, "Tuzemsky rum", whose traditions in our country go back to the 19th century, our producers had to rename it "Tuzemak".
Only products made from cane distillate can be called rum, not sugar beet.
The official list of registered products of the EU, along with the world-famous "feta" and "gorgonzol" cheeses, marzipan from the German Lübeck or Parma ham, has already been, for example, Karlovy Vary sausages, Gorzhelya and Trzebny carp and Zhatta.
The Pardubice Gingerbread and the Gorgie Pipes are also proud of their EU trademark.
