MVRDV architects prove that real adventures are not just in the imagination - Spekkenisse and his newly built Book Mountain - 2 photos
"I think the building is fun, it looks futuristic, we finally have something interesting to see again", says Lisette Verhaig, walking along the road.
And Stefan Spermon, an IT specialist at a large company nearby, says, "No, this building is really beautiful".
But I ask myself, why do we need another library today?
Everyone has the Internet, iPads, and e-books.
Nobody volunteers for old-fashioned libraries anymore, right?
Speikennisse, a sleepy little town near Rotterdam, holds an unusual record.
Its population of 80,000 has the lowest level of education in the Netherlands.
To combat this unfortunate situation, it was decided some years ago to contribute to the general education system by building seven fictitious bridges, which are depicted on the euro banknotes as colorful miniatures of reinforced concrete.
The success of this enlightenment initiative was modest.
And then the town fathers realized that the only way they had left to beat the statistics was to build a library here!
Vini Maas of the Rotterdam architectural bureau MVRDV, master of bold column diagrams and the author of witty, sometimes even cynical constructions, took on the task with his usual composure and appeared at the competition audition in 2003 with five books under his mouse and a grin on his face.
As the jury looked around and shook their heads, the impudent Maas built a pyramid out of his original gift and concluded his defense of the project with the words: "Dear citizens!"
Here it is, my proposal: "Book Mountain" in Speknisse, the so called Buchenberg!
Nine years later, this mountain worth 30 million euros has grown.
It is part of a revitalization project that also includes an underground garage, a supermarket, a post office, and several adjacent residential buildings and townhouses totaling 50 apartments.
In early November, "Knijnsberg" was awarded the second prize of the "Best Library of the Netherlands 2012" competition.
The project also participates in the Dutch national competition for wooden structures in 2012.
Thus, the faceless suburb that previously offered nothing but a postmodern pedestrian zone and a surprisingly ugly town hall, whose white facades evoke the idea of a dairy, has become richer in one modern architectural work.
But the most important thing is that in Spaykeniss the first public building of cultural significance in the history of this town appeared.
The long road to the book
First impression: a book El Dorado under the cheese cover.
There is only one elevator, which runs through the center of the mountain range, so true fans of architecture and reading will prefer to explore the area on foot.
The light-filled, easily visible glassed-in building, its hard-painted floors, and its elegant street lamps all create the unmistakable feeling of a public city square.
The urban environment is perfectly recreated.
The eye is searching for benches, dogs, and boys and girls playing soccer.
And everywhere, books, books, books.
"Usually the bookshelves are along the facades, and in the middle is a large dark room, usually uncomfortable and faceless", says Vini Maas.
We've turned the classic configuration of space upside down and pulled the reading area inward.
The interior of the book mountain is well-used: the center has offices, an Internet library, a chess club, an environmental center, and technical facilities.
Especially pleasing are the black bookshelves, which serve as walls, railings, and stair rails.
They have a unique look, texture, and smell.
Even the most experienced architects and civil engineers are puzzled by this unknown material.
"We were looking to work with recycled materials", explains Joop Trauborst, the project manager representing the community of Spekenisse, in accordance with the requirements of the standard.
And once, on an agricultural farm in Frisland, we found a suitable by-product of farming.
For many years, in greenhouses and fields in the Netherlands, artificial fibrous material of millimetre thickness has been used as a root pad.
It's cheap and it saves time.
Thin textiles are good for a season or two, after which they can be thrown away.
For the library, this canvas -- the first of its kind -- was pressed into a four-centimeter-thick panel.
Under the action of heat and pressure, the so-called landbauplastic (KLP) is transformed into a dark, uniform, durable material, with a smell a little like a new car and a little like a pair of sneakers.
There are 105 steps to the top.
Anyone who makes the 500-mile journey will be rewarded at the literary café with not only fantastic views of the city but also with Dutch croquettes and wood ficus in pots.
They take care of the atmosphere, and first of all the right humidity of the air on the literary mountain.
The cost of a new soul
"It's hard to believe, but this building, despite its many glass surfaces, is an example of an ecological project", says Troeborst.
The earth's heat is used to heat and cool it.
Although the Book Mountain is covered with a glass cover, even on clear days the sun only shines inside for a short time.
The wide cork-wood farms, perpendicular to the glass facade, provide shade and absorb most of the sun's rays.
The climate in the room is very pleasant.
The rest of the protection is provided by fully automatic rolling curtains.
Stefan Spermon, the IT skeptic mentioned earlier, has already visited the new library.
Lisette Verhaeghe was here too.
And also a professor of traditional Chinese medicine, Cynthia Bogard, who called Buckenberg "the Speknisses soul that has long been missing".
The reason: A few weeks before the opening, each resident was invited to donate one book from his or her congregation.
These books were to fill the empty shelves of the not-yet-fully-stocked library - at that time it contained 70,000 books.
It worked.
The regiments are all set up.
"There is nothing worse than a half-empty library", says architect Vini Maas.
"I think that because of our invitation, every resident is now connected in some way to this new house.
Everyone knows that his book is part of this building.
Even if it's only for decoration.
So MVRDV has solved the royal task, which in professional jargon is called creating an identity.
Speikennisse wrote his literary history.
And they're very young and uneducated.
It's just a starting point for building an identity.
Sabo: "Germans should play a more important role"
Germany abstained in the vote on the recognition of Palestine.
In the opinion of Stefan Sabo, an expert on U.S.-European relations, by doing so, Berlin is balancing on a diplomatic tightrope.
Deutsche Welle: Germany first made it clear earlier this week that it would vote against the Palestinian bid for observer status at the United Nations.
But then Berlin abstained.
Why? Why?
Stefan Sabo: Germany does not support the actions of the Israelis in Gaza.
Now Germany needs to be careful about its special relationship with Israel.
But at the same time, I believe that it also does not support the American position.
Germany wanted to demonstrate its independence - without being too critical of Israel.
During the March 2011 uprising in Libya, Germany also abstained from voting on the introduction of a no-fly zone.
NATO eventually made this offer.
Is it difficult for Germany to take a clear position on complex international issues?
Yes, it is.
The fact is that it is in the process of transforming its foreign policy, namely, moving from a policy that was, so to speak, run by the United States, to a German foreign policy.
The situation is further complicated by the fact that Europeans do not have a common policy.
So the Germans are again caught between two fronts.
They're expected to play a more independent role, but they're not used to it.
I believe that while they are only beginning to play their role, they are on the way to a "more normal" foreign policy.
The kind of foreign policy that France or the UK have.
What exactly does "normal" foreign policy mean from a German point of view?
It is the willingness to take a position in your national interest that is not dependent on the position of the United States or your European partners.
I believe that German foreign policy depends on economic policy, that is, on exports and links with certain regions, such as Russia, China or the Middle East.
Germany's economic interests are very different from those of other large states, and Germany must therefore protect its own interests.
Did these economic interests influence the position in the Middle East conflict and the UN vote?
First, Germany has major markets in the Middle East, particularly the Gulf states.
So she needs to be careful not to offend the public and the elites in the Arab world.
Either way, it plays a role.
But I wouldn't put too much stock in it, it's not a completely one-way communication.
But in any case, it plays an important role in the calculations of the Germans.
Did Germany hurt its relationship with the United States by abstaining on important decisions, such as the Palestinian vote?
I am sure that in Europe and even in the United States, the German position is being understood.
So I don't think it was as dramatic as the Libyan issue.
Perhaps Germany will even gain some respect.
It signals that it should be taken seriously as a player in the international arena and that its interests should be considered.
There are different opinions in Europe about the Palestinian initiative.
The US, on the other hand, has clearly vetoed it.
Is there a disagreement between the United States and many European countries?
Because of American domestic policy, these differences have always existed.
I think that the Obama administration has a deep understanding of the European position.
But given the political situation in the country, the government cannot take such a position openly.
I believe that the significant differences in opinion are not at all as significant as they always seem.
If you look at the relationship between Obama and Prime Minister Netanyahu, you'll notice that Obama is not at all fond of Netanyahu's policies.
Is it easy for Germany to combine its close ties with Israel and the US on the one hand and its status as a key partner in the EU on the other?
I think that's what makes it so difficult for the Germans.
Of course, the Germans would have been a little bit easier if there had been a unified, uncontroversial European policy, but that's not the case now.
So they can't speak to the larger picture and instead have to act on their own vision of the situation.
That's what they're doing with the euro.
I think that in the future Germany will take a leading role in the formulation of a common European position.
It's not easy for Germany, at least because of its ties to Israel.
It's always been a touchy subject.
But I think the Germans understand that they have to play a more independent role.
If Germany sees itself as an important international player, will it not really take the lead?
Or is Germany still struggling to take the lead?
Germany is not used to this, it is still always unpleasant and, for obvious reasons, it is still always difficult to play a significant role.
Take the euro crisis, for example, where every time Germany takes a big role, there are all kinds of anti-German sentiments.
The Germans are not easily able to cope with this.
Actually, it's an old problem: you don't want to be surrounded by hostile countries.
From this point of view, Germany is in a much more difficult position than the United States.
She has to consider the different neighbors and opinions, and that's not easy.
So, the US influence in European politics is steadily declining, but at the moment the EU is not filling that vacuum, so who is left?
The Germans will simply have to play a more significant role.
Even if you don't like it, or it's unpleasant or it makes you feel unloved, that's life!
Stefan Szabo is the deputy director of the Transatlantic Academy in Washington, D.C., an institute where academics and political scientists from Europe and North America collaborate on research on the transatlantic community.
In addition, Szabo is a member of the German Marshall Foundation, where he specializes in German politics, U.S. foreign policy, and transatlantic relations.
China's "trademark protection": when Puma and Armani suddenly become Chinese
Armani is a world-famous brand, and Polo Ralph Lauren is too.
But what is Armani Polo?
It's a fully registered name in China, which has nothing to do with the companies it's derived from.
However, it will be protected until the owners of the original names file a lawsuit.
But it's still unclear whether they'll be able to assert their rights.
"It's becoming increasingly difficult for foreigners to defend their trademarks in China", says Thomas Patloch, a lawyer at Taylor Wessing who specializes in trademark infringement cases in the Far East.
I have a new case like this on my desk every week.
For copycats, it's just a matter of adding a couple of letters to get the right to register their trademarks.
So from Gucci you get Lu-Gucci, instead of Prada you can register Prada-Kny.
German companies, such as sports goods manufacturer Puma, are being legally copied in this way.
Patloche opens the file with records from the Beijing Trademark Office.
On 14 September 2010, the Chinese company registered the trademark Zegna DF Puma, an artificial name that also uses the name of the fashion house Ermenegildo Zegna.
The Chinese are the world champions in copyright infringement.
In the big cities there are department stores with many floors, selling almost exclusively counterfeits.
But Pattolach's case is not like that, for he opposes the idea that Chinese companies should be granted the right to use a trademark that is already protected elsewhere.
The Chinese call it "ban minpai", the mark of a passenger.
This word is associated with "ban daquan".
It's a nickname for women who go after rich men.
Chinese authorities deny any involvement
"It's damaging to business, and it needs to be addressed", Patloch believes.
"The brand is being eroded, the unique position is being lost, the image is being hurt very badly".
The financial losses and the procedural costs in the affected industries are estimated in the millions, especially in the case of expensive copied products.
According to market research firm CLSA, China is the third largest and fastest growing luxury goods market, with sales of 15 billion euros a year.
However, it is difficult and expensive to obtain the deletion of questionable entries in the register of trademarks.
The process can take up to nine years, with no clear outcome.
Patloch tells of cases in which the court rejected claims, since after a long time the contested name became "the reality of the market".
If the plaintiff is unsuccessful, he will even have to pay the plagiarist, since he damaged his trademark in China, Patloch says.
Sometimes the law of the jungle rules.
There are also famous cases of graphic elements.
In 2009, Daimler lost a court case against construction machinery manufacturer Sany, which had recently acquired concrete pump manufacturer Putzmeister.
So the Chinese still have the right to use the Mercedes star.
The company that bought Volvo, Geely, originally used a blue-and-white logo that resembled BMW; the process was successful, and Geely had to change it.
Fashion goods maker Lacoste lost in China to imitators from Hong Kong and Singapore, who had the famous crocodile look the other way.
The Chinese authorities do not consider themselves to be at fault.
The CTMO's trademark office in Beijing confirms that in 2010 there were difficulties due to lack of staff and equipment.
But last year, there was a "return to normalcy in the workflow from an emergency".
The number of pending objections dropped by 22 percent.
Nearly 57,000 such cases were closed, a 75 percent increase over the previous year.
However, at least 81,500 claims are still pending in the department.
It 's costly to fight .
As is often the case in China, the numbers are staggering.
Last year, the CTMO received more than 1.4 million trademark applications, almost a third more than in 2010.
The record means that China has topped the list of new registrations worldwide for the tenth consecutive year, the agency said.
The same goes for the total number of valid trademarks, only 5.5 million.
In 2011, 1.8 billion yuan of fees were paid.
Simply put, this means that each registration costs an average of 1,280 yuan, or 160 euros.
Protesting against it is worth many times more, as the case of the German family business Freudenberg shows.
For more than seven years, the concern has been fighting against the Chinese plagiarist.
The Germans were able to get the illegal production of counterfeit car parts to stop.
