Facts about sexually transmitted infections
What are the most important sexually transmitted diseases?
Bacterial STIs include syphilis, chlamydia, and gonorrhea.
The most common viral STIs are HIV, human papillomavirus, genital herpes, and hepatitis.
The lobular pediculosis and scabies are parasitic STIs.
What are the main groups affected?
Syphilis and gonorrhea are mostly found in men who have sex with men.
The Robert Koch Institute estimates that at least four out of every five cases of syphilis in Germany are transmitted by sexual contact between men.
Among heterosexual adults, the most common sexually transmitted diseases are chlamydia, trichomoniasis, candidiasis, gonorrhea, and human papillomavirus.
The HIV prevalence among heterosexual adults is relatively low, but they account for about 20 percent of new HIV infections.
Chlamydia infections are much more common among young people than other population groups.
European data show that three quarters of all infections affect young people aged 15 to 25.
We also have a high incidence of human papillomavirus among young people.
How is the number of cases of infection changing?
Not all sexually transmitted diseases are subject to registration.
The incidence of syphilis, according to the Robert Koch Institute, more than doubled from 1,697 cases in 2001 to 3,698 cases in 2011.
The number of new HIV infections has been declining since 2007.
In 2011, there were about 2700 cases.
That's about one tenth less than last year.
What symptoms indicate a sexually transmitted disease?
Infectious diseases may cause genital ulcers, urinary complaints, discharge, lower abdominal pain, and blisters or thickening.
However, they often go unnoticed and are not accompanied by pain or other symptoms.
How can you protect yourself?
Condoms can reduce the risk of infection, but they do not offer 100% protection.
In fact, some sexually transmitted diseases can also be spread through contact and close physical contact.
So experts recommend regular checkups, especially if you have frequently switched partners.
Early diagnosis can cure most STIs and avoid long-term consequences.
