We don't like to be seen, we don't brag.
Norway is very careful with its oil - much of the oil and gas industry's income is invested in a special fund set up for the benefit of future generations.
In the years before the global financial crisis, when everyone was spending money they didn't have, Norway was very conservative in calculating its costs.
"As long as you can ski in the winter and hike in the summer, that's enough to make you happy", says Anna.
"And there's the raccoon", she adds with a carefree laugh.
I'm standing in line for some food in the snow - I'm tired of the shrimp.
This is a moose burger, which is definitely an exotic, delicious, juicy meat.
But in the evening, we will be greeted by even more of the same fish, with a memorable aroma.
There's a special fish-of-the-river dinner at my hotel where the guests vote on the best or perhaps the most fragrant fish.
It's a live TV broadcast of a butterfly-tie anchor surrounded by plates of crabfish.
This is like the Eurovision Song Contest.
"Then, Thor-Jurgen, what is your estimate of the best fish in your mountains?"
"Yes, Howard, this is our rating"...
Everyone laughs and applauds.
Someone falls off a chair, possibly from overdosing on aquavit.
Or maybe just by inhaling the scent of this fish.
Mexican President Enrique Peña Nieto is about to embark on a difficult career.
As Mexico's newly elected President Enrique Peña Nieto prepares to take office, BBC correspondent Will Grant invites us to take a look at the challenges he will face and the mixed expectations of his country's people.
Traffic in Mexico City is in a particularly bad state right now.
This city is congested with traffic at its best, and since Monday, steel barriers have been erected, cutting off several key highways to the capital and causing chaos on the roads.
However, this was not to stop people from going to work from the suburbs, but to prevent the protesters from getting to the parliament building.
On Sunday, Mexico's new leader, Enrique Peña Nieto, will take the presidential oath and assume the reins of government.
He has a difficult task ahead of him.
Mexico has made good economic progress under the administration of Felipe Calderon, who is now stepping down, but the country is mired in a drug war that has already claimed some 60,000 lives in six years.
"My government is declaring to the people of Mexico its commitment to combat violence", Mr. Peña Nieto told U.S. President Barack Obama earlier this week in the Oval Office of the White House.
I'm going to propose a new security strategy that will allow us to achieve that goal.
Prior to his statements alongside the US president, Mr Pena Nieto's political career had been as governor of his home state of Mexico.
In his homeland, the vast state surrounding the capital was divided over the new leader.
A man of integrity .
In the idyllic town of Val-de-Bravo, for example, he is remembered with warmth.
Residents credit him with reviving tourism, developing the resort area and creating infrastructure.
The town is reached by one of the new highways built by Mr. Peña Nieto, which are markedly different from the roads with potholes and pits that were previously on the site.
His name is on a plaque on the modern sports center building and on an impressive interactive museum dedicated to climate change.
"We are hoping for real and serious change with him", says his friend and political ally, Gabriel Olvera Hernández, a state congressman for the Institutional Revolutionary Party (PRI) led by Peña Nieto.
We expect the real and decisive changes that our country so desperately needs, primarily in the areas of security and economic development.
After 81 years of continuous rule, the PRI was ousted in 2000 by Vicente Fox.
Congressman Olvera admits that after his 12 years of absence from the Los Pinos presidential palace, the party has high hopes for Enrique Peña Nieto.
He also refutes the allegations of ineffectiveness that the opposition has made against the new president.
He's very straightforward and very committed to his vision for the future of the country.
He's a great statesman, and above all, a great listener.
But in another part of the state, many people have a different idea of the former governor.
The municipality of Nessauaalcoyotl, also known as Ciudad Nesa, is the most striking contrast to the cobbled streets of Valle de Bravo.
Hidden beneath the overpasses of the highways, it is in many ways a suburb of Mexico City itself.
And the problems in the municipality are also of a severe nature in this metropolis.
Troops were deployed earlier this year to quell drug gangs in the area; violence against women is particularly acute.
In the past two years alone, dozens of women have been found dead in the desert near a vast landfill.
More than a thousand women were murdered in Mexico State during the governorship of Mr. Peña Nieto - far more than in the notoriously violent Ciudad Juárez, which has become a byword for the murder of innocent women.
Mr. Peña Nieto's opponents say that he has failed to address the issue of female homicide during his time as governor.
At worst, his administration is accused of completely ignoring the problem.
A resident of a concrete house, similar to most houses in this dilapidated area, Irineia Buendia barely holds back tears as she shows me photos of her deceased daughter Mariana Luna.
According to the official version, Mariana committed suicide in 2010.
However, her family believes that she was killed by her roommate.
"When I got to her house, it was as if her body had been washed", recalls Ms. Buendia.
There were signs of a beating, and the body was already decomposed.
Mariana's mother tells the story, and her portrait looks at us from the wall, where it hangs next to a crucifix with just one word on it: justice.
That's what they say this family was denied.
"I was treated by state officials as an old gossip, a disgruntled disturber.
They want people to just believe everything they say and keep quiet.
But it's wrong, it's not right, especially when there are so many violations and shortcomings", she says.
By wearing the presidential vest on Saturday, President Peña Nieto will take on a heavy responsibility along with her.
Tens of thousands of families in Mexico have been affected by violent crime in the past six years, and the new president has promised to make it a priority during his term.
"I hope he will be the same president as he was as governor", says Olvera, a congressman from Valle de Bravo for the PRI.
However, this is what the families of the victims in Ciudad Nesa fear most.
Bradley Manning did not complain of ill-treatment, the prosecution claims.
Prosecutors are trying to disprove Bradley Manning's claims of poor detention conditions.
During the hearing, the focus was on Manning's time in the military prison at Quantico, Virginia.
The defense is requesting a mistrial on the grounds that Manning's detention was cruel and unusual.
A U.S. Army private is accused of stealing several thousand classified documents.
On Friday, the prosecution sought to prove that Private Bradley Manning, accused of the largest classified leak in U.S. history, had missed numerous opportunities to complain about the mistreatment he said he had suffered while in military prison.
During cross-examination at a pretrial hearing at Fort Meade, Maryland, military prosecutor Major Ashden Fane stated that the records of Manning's weekly visits by prison officials during his nine months of confinement at Quantico, Virginia, contained no complaints of ill-treatment.
The cross-examination, in the context of the defense's motion to dismiss Manning's case on the grounds that the conditions of his detention were cruel and in themselves sufficient punishment, was held the day after Manning stated that he intended to commit suicide while in custody.
A military intelligence analyst arrested in June 2010 is accused of stealing thousands of classified documents while serving in Iraq.
These materials were subsequently published online on the website WikiLeaks.
WikiLeaks has not confirmed that Manning was the source of the information.
During Friday's hearing, prosecutor Fein, along with Manning, reviewed the records that were filled out by Manning's visiting administration officials during his time at Quantico Prison, where he was held under house arrest from July 2010 to April 2011.
During these visits, prison officials asked Manning questions and recorded his answers.
When prosecutor Feyn asked about the reports on Friday, Manning acknowledged that he rated the treatment he received from the prison administration as "excellent" and the overall conditions of detention as "very professionally organized".
The reviewed reports contain no complaints of ill-treatment, despite the fact that Manning was directly asked about his conditions of detention, Fein argues.
Manning replied that he had expressed his concerns verbally and that administration officials who visited him had discussed the issues with him and said they would address them, but had not put them in writing.
"They recorded 'no problems' (after discussing my complaints), but that doesn't mean I didn't bring it up in conversation", Manning says.
The military judge, Colonel Denise Lind, also asked Manning why he had not complained of the ill-treatment in January 2011 during a commission hearing on the suicidal intentions he had expressed in writing months earlier.
Manning replied that during that meeting, he wanted to get his "trauma warning" removed and his prison sentence reduced.
Military officials explained that the limited detention regime - a level below the suicide prevention surveillance regime - was introduced to protect the prisoner and also for the safety of others.
"I wanted to let the administration know that I was okay, that they would lift the trauma prevention regime... that my standard of living would improve, from my perspective", Manning explained.
On Thursday, Manning testified about his arrest in Iraq and transfer to Kuwait, where he was held for nearly two months before being transferred to a prison at the Naval Base at Quantico, Virginia, in July 2010.
He said that he had suicidal thoughts while in Kuwait, and that one day he lost consciousness because of the extreme heat.
He explained that it was psychologically very difficult when you're not told how your destiny is being decided, and what's going on in the outside world.
"My world has shrunk to the size of Camp Arifjan, to the size of my prison", Manning said Thursday.
- I thought I was gonna die in this cage".
While in Quantico, Manning said he spent most of his time in a small cell - at least 21 hours, and often more than 23 hours a day - in total isolation.
Manning reports that he was allowed to leave only a mattress, blanket, spandex, a few items of clothing and glasses.
He says he tried to move, because sleeping or even just lying down during the daytime was against the rules.
Manning said that during his sleep, he was constantly hit in the eyes by light from outside the chamber.
If the guards did not see his face when he turned over in bed at night, he said he was awakened and made to turn over on his back.
Manning's attorney filed a formal objection to Manning's wrongful treatment in January 2011.
In April 2011, Manning was transferred to the military prison at Fort Leavenworth, Kansas.
In addition, on Friday, the judge questioned Manning about a statement he made during Thursday's deposition that after being forced to sleep naked in his cell at Quantico one night, he was forced to stand naked in front of guards and other inmates at the morning check.
Manning said he had no way to cover himself with a blanket during the sweep.
Responding to questions from the judge on Friday, Manning said he understood from the guard's order that he should throw away a blanket that could cover him, but admitted that no one had specifically ordered him to throw it away.
On Thursday, Manning said he was forced to sleep naked the night before for trying to show the officer that he was no threat.
Manning reported that he told the officer that he could have used a rubber hose or a spanking to injure himself, but did not do so.
That night, Manning testified that his underwear, shorts and glasses were taken from his cell.
His lawyers hope the judge will at least consider what he endured while in prison and significantly reduce his sentence if Manning is convicted by a military court, which is due to start hearing his case early next year.
The defense said it plans to propose Manning plead guilty to lesser charges and dispute other charges as excessive.
The resumption of the hearing is scheduled for this weekend, and the prosecution is expected to insist that the conditions of detention were justified.
The Pentagon claims that Manning was held at Quantico under the most stringent rules for detainees.
Among the charges against Manning are aiding the enemy, unlawfully facilitating the publication of data on the Internet, transmitting information related to national defense, and the theft of state property or documents.
If he's convicted on all counts, he could face life in prison.
My national crisis is the story of a Mexican-American.
According to the author, many Mexicans were forced to leave Mexico due to the lack of opportunities to realize themselves.
Mexicans tend to blame those who left because they remind the country of difficult times.
Rubén Navarrete believes that Mexican-Americans are torn between two cultures.
On a recent trip to Mexico City, I walked down the arrivals hallway, approached the border control area, and froze in place.
The signs indicated two lines: one for Mexicanos (Mexicans), the other for Extranjeros (foreigners).
I stood in front of them for a few seconds, not knowing where to go.
I grew up in central California, and I've been called Mexican all my life.
It's just a term, like my friends in Boston call themselves Irish, and my friends in New York call themselves Italian.
Later, I settled on the complex construction of "Mexican-American".
But here I was in Mexico.
Here, in my grandfather's homeland, there was no need for conventional names or complex constructions.
I was just an American.
I speak Spanish well enough to ask questions or answer them.
But my vocabulary is poorer than native speakers, and I can't get rid of my American accent.
So I got my American passport and got in line for Extranjeros.
I remembered this story a few days ago when Mexico's newly elected president, Enrique Peña Nieto, visited the White House and met with President Obama.
The agenda included the usual issues for the presidents of these countries: immigration, drugs and trade.
President Peña Nieto has talked about the rise of the Mexican economy, which means that Mexicans can now, with the same success, stay in Mexico instead of moving to the United States.
He wants to sign a partnership agreement with the U.S. and Canada and create a North American trade bloc like the European Union.
In addition, President Peña Nieto promised to continue the war against drug cartels in Mexico, but no specific proposals were made.
For Mexico, relations with the United States are a difficult and long-standing issue.
Most Americans never thought that in 1848, the United States invaded Mexico and, at the barrel of a gun, forced its leaders to give up half their territory.
But Mexicans think in centuries, not minutes, and they see the memory of those events in everything.
So when any U.S. official says a word of criticism toward Mexico, the press and the Mexican elite are quick to complain that the Americans are encroaching on the sovereignty of their neighbors.
And the descendants of Montezuma are full of war.
The most complex of these is Mexico's relationship with the more than 35 million Mexican-Americans living in the United States.
You want to talk about grievances?
There's enough of them.
In Mexico, there are winners and losers, people who find opportunities in this country and people who don't.
In Los Angeles, in Las Vegas, in Phoenix, in Denver, in San Antonio, there are so many people of Mexican descent for one reason: at some point in their family history, someone -- a father or a grandfather -- didn't have the opportunity to make a living in Mexico and had to go north.
Most of the time, they were Mexicans of a certain type -- dark, poorly educated, from poor peasant families.
We are their descendants, and we remember it.
In Mexico, they see it differently.
Today, our lives are the embodiment of the American dream, and we've gone to good schools and got good jobs, but we must never forget that even this dream is American, not Mexican.
Our national identity is confused and unclear, but we know which country to call our own.
The United States of America.
Besides, we know that most of the Mexican elite and the ruling class don't like us.
We're giving them the same answer.
They see us as a reminder of their humiliating defeat and treat us as second-class citizens, not true Mexicans.
We don't speak Spanish well enough, and our ties with Mexico aren't strong enough.
Our very existence is a failure to them.
If our ancestors had succeeded in Mexico, they wouldn't have left.
We wouldn't be behind the silk curtain, finding a life in the U.S.A. and losing our spiritual connections.
My wife was born in Guadalajara and moved to the United States legally as a child, and it reminds me that there are certain frictions between real Mexicans and Mexican-Americans -- that Mexicans have a clear sense of their national identity, and Mexican-Americans are offended by that.
She's a U.S. citizen and she feels she belongs to both of those countries.
At the same time, many of the Mexican Americans I know don't feel like they belong to any of them.
We listen to the Mexican band Los Tigres del Norte, but we also like Bruce Springsteen.
Getting the best of both worlds, you inevitably lose your roots.
In Mexico, we are Americans.
And in the U.S., we're called Mexicans.
Now, as I discovered during my visit, as if our relations weren't already complicated enough, some Mexican leaders and intellectuals want to repair relations with the diaspora.
They want Mexican-Americans to act as a sort of ambassador for Mexico and represent its interests in the United States.
We could tell our American friends what a beautiful country this is and how great it is to visit, and we could convince political leaders to strengthen ties with Mexico.
Yeah, of course.
It's not gonna work.
Too much of a past.
And given the gap between rich and poor, the rampant corruption and drug trafficking, many of us don't think this country is all that beautiful.
Sorry, but you're on your own, amigos.
And that's only fair.
If some Mexicans still cannot forgive the United States for what it did to Mexico a century and a half ago, they will have to accept the fact that some Mexican-Americans still resent the way their relatives were treated in Mexico not so long ago.
I know.
I guess we have more in common than I thought.
Old battles in the new Middle East
A ceasefire between Israel and Hamas could be a fragile foundation for future peace
Is a lasting peace between Arabs and Israelis in the Middle East possible?
Another round of bloodshed is leading to the conclusion that such hopes are futile.
There are the familiar, pointless arguments about who started it; the destruction of many buildings; the deaths of more than 140 Palestinians, most of them civilians, and six Israelis; and, for the first time in the conflict, rockets fired from Gaza have landed in the vicinity of Israel's capital, Tel Aviv, and the holy city of Jerusalem.
But despite the fact that Israelis and Palestinians are hopelessly mired in their age-old conflict, change has come to the Middle East.
One can react to this in different ways, but the events of the "Arab Spring" have swept many established realities into a rebellious storm, and Palestinians and Israelis have not been able to stay out of the storm that has shaken the region.
Perhaps as a result, their fight will be even more bloody than before.
But there are reasons for hope in this deadly impasse.
A War Without a Winner
At first glance, the situation does not give cause for optimism.
Even if the ceasefire signed on November 21 is enforced, this week's clashes have only strengthened the position of the security forces on both sides.
Leaders of the Islamist Hamas movement, which came to power in the Gaza Strip in 2007, claim that they forced Israel to retreat despite the losses they had suffered.
Despite the fact that some of the group's leaders have been killed and 1.7 million people are trapped in one of the most populous and troubled parts of the world, Israel has not been able to destroy Hamas.
In fact, Hamas is growing its popularity in the West Bank, another Palestinian territory currently controlled by the more moderate Fatah movement.
Moreover, Hamas leaders may well conclude that time is on their side.
As Islamist movements grow in influence in the Arab world, Hamas is gaining new influential and wealthy friends.
A rising regional leader, Turkey, once Israel's closest ally among Muslim countries, has come out in support of Hamas; Qatar, one of the Gulf's richest and most dynamic states, has followed suit.
Celebratory Hamas supporters claim to have created an Islamist crescent around Israel - from Lebanon in the north, ruled by the militant Hezbollah group, to Syria, where increasingly pro-Islamist rebels are poised to topple Bashar al-Assad, to Jordan, where the king's authority is threatened by Hamas allies.
The most significant shift in the balance of power in the region occurred on Israel's southern border, in the most populous and important Arab country, Egypt, where the Muslim Brotherhood movement gained strength under President Mohamed Morsi.
Hosni Mubarak, who ruled Egypt for 30 years and was ousted in 2011, was a secular dictator who paid little attention to supporting Hamas.
The Muslim Brotherhood, on the other hand, is an organization that is very similar to Hamas, and its leaders are more populist.
In future diplomatic arrangements, Hamas could become a significant player whose voice cannot be silenced even by Israel and America.
At the same time, hardliners in Israel will come to the opposite conclusion.
Hamas was defeated militarily.
The Iron Dome missile defense system was cost-effective and successfully destroyed many of the Hamas missiles launched.
The citizens of Israel can sleep well, at least for a while.
As for diplomacy, the US has remained true to its unchanging stance; many European countries have also blamed Hamas for starting the latest round of violence.
Another important factor is Israel's economic prosperity, especially under the government of Benjamin Netanyahu, which has largely ignored the peace process.
Despite the deaths of some 30 Israelis from rockets fired from Gaza since 2004, Israel has managed to minimize the problem of suicide bombers, in part by building a wall that encroaches on the West Bank - a significant part of the unrecognized Palestinian state - and protects Jewish settlements that continue to expand despite the illegality of such actions under international law.
Prime Minister Netanyahu, whose Likud party has teamed up with an even more aggressive conservative, Avigdor Lieberman, in preparation for the January 22 elections, is in a comfortable position.
What's the point of flattering the Palestinians and giving them their own state?
If you give them the power in the West Bank, won't they start firing rockets at Israel, like their brothers in the Gaza Strip?
It's best to keep them on the wall and to stifle any attempt to raise their heads.
The hardliners may win; however, their calculations may be overturned by the Arab Spring.
With Islamists coming to power in Egypt and elsewhere feeling less than warm feelings towards Israel, their priority will be domestic issues.
Israel's defense budget is larger than all of its Arab neighbors combined.
Going to war with a regional superpower is unlikely to help Arab governments strengthen their own economies.
The pragmatism of the Egyptian president, Morsi, who worked with Barack Obama on a ceasefire, is a good sign and could signal the beginning of a change.
Israel, no less, must consider the long-term consequences of its policies.
As democratic change begins to take hold in Arab countries, the denial of Palestinian self-determination is a time bomb that will eventually explode in the occupied territories, like the bus bombing in Tel Aviv this week.
The repression is already undermining the foundations of the democratic order in the Jewish state, and the demographic aspect - the growth of the Arab population - is only exacerbating these problems.
The bloodshed that occurs every few years in the Gaza Strip to suppress Hamas is paying the price of growing international discontent.
Both sides need an external impulse.
There remains one solution, one that has been repeatedly called for by the sane representatives on both sides, as well as much of the rest of the world and our newspaper: the formation of two states and the ceding of territories to Israel in exchange for security.
The hope remains, not too impressive in the short term, that a cease-fire will allow other countries to have a more effective influence on the parties to the conflict.
Egypt, which has long since decided to cut off its arms supplies to the Gaza Strip, and Turkey and Qatar are in an unprecedentedly advantageous position to persuade Hamas to recognize the borders of the Jewish state, which have been agreed since 1967, with the exchange of territories and the shared use of Jerusalem.
Other Arab countries should also make efforts to reconcile Hamas and Fatah.
This would do more for the creation of a Palestinian state than the upcoming UN vote, which could result in the recognition of a virtual state of Palestine.
President Obama has a role to play in getting Israel to the negotiating table.
During his first term, he never presented his own peace plan.
After returning to the White House, he still shows a reluctance to get involved in the problem.
That is a catastrophically short-sighted position.
The United States has a vital interest in stability in the Middle East.
That's only possible with a peace agreement between Israel and the Palestinians.
Australia has introduced a uniform packaging law for cigarettes.
Warnings about the harm of smoking and the depiction of diseased body parts are contrasted on the dull green boxes, the same for all brands of cigarettes.
Australia's first-ever uniform packaging law for cigarettes and tobacco products took effect, replacing the logos and color scheme of different brands with a uniform olive-coloured box with gruesome images of diseased body parts and children whose health has been compromised by their parents' smoking.
Apart from the different pictures and inscriptions warning about the dangers of smoking, the only difference between the packages, introduced in the mandatory order from this Saturday, is the name of the stamps, which are printed in the same small font.
These are the most stringent regulations in the world for tobacco packaging.
The federal government of Australia says that the measure is designed to discourage young people from smoking, thus stripping the habit of its fashionable status.
The decision was based on research showing that 99 out of 100 people who did not start smoking before age 26 never became smokers.
"It's clear that even at a very young age, children understand the meaning that tobacco companies are trying to convey through the packaging", explains Health Minister Tanja Pliberec, citing studies that have shown that, for example, the crown in the logo is associated with the idea of a princess in children.
Australia is one of the countries with the lowest smoking rates in the world, so these changes will not have a major impact on the profits of multinational corporations, although other countries are considering similar measures.
The tobacco industry was strongly opposed to the law.
Tobacco companies argue that this will only increase the black market, where cheap and affordable cigarettes will be sold.
"This bill will have a far more serious impact than the people who originally proposed it had in mind", says Scott McIntyre, a spokesman for British American Tobacco in Australia.
Fake manufacturers from China and Indonesia will supply many more of these goods to sell on the streets of Australia.
For some, on the contrary, the new laws have helped to grow their businesses.
Sandra Ha of the small family-owned company Zico Import Pty Ltd claims that the demand for ports and silicone cases to hide the objectionable images on the packaging has increased rapidly (from almost zero) since two months ago when companies such as British American Tobacco, British Imperial Tobacco, Philip Morris and Japan Tobacco lost a case in the High Court of Australia where they tried to appeal the law.
According to Sandra Ha, Zico has already sold about six thousand items to wholesale businesses and is waiting for a new batch.
It's good business for us.
A potential obstacle to the effectiveness of such measures, according to experts, is the popularity of social media among the very population targeted by the measures.
After a series of laws were passed in Australia that made it illegal to advertise cigarettes on television and to promote sports events, and that prohibited vendors from displaying cigarettes in public, tobacco advertising moved to the Internet.
The Australian government has banned local companies and websites from advertising online, but it cannot restrict foreign websites from doing so.
"If you're a tobacco salesman and you have this one small loophole, the idea of promoting your product online is very tempting", explains Becky Freeman, a public health researcher at the University of Sydney.
Freeman notes the rise of brand reviews written by so-called ordinary users on social media sites like YouTube, Twitter and Facebook.
The question is, is this really the work of a private citizen who loves Marlboro cigarettes so much that he took the time and effort to make a video, or is it the work of an advertising company?
British American Tobacco's Australian branch claims that the industry is now more busy adapting to the new regulations than advertising.
Tobacco industry representatives have gone as far as sponsoring Ukraine, Honduras, and the Dominican Republic to challenge the new rules: These nations are filing claims with the World Trade Organization, claiming that trade has been unfairly restricted, even though all of these countries have very little trade with Australia.
A decision by the WTO is expected by mid-2013.
Tanni Plibbersek said the government has been discussing with other countries the possibility of adopting similar packaging laws.
In 2001, Canada became the first country to make it mandatory to post pictures warning of the dangers of smoking.
This rule has now been adopted in more than 40 countries, including Brazil, Turkey, and Ukraine.
The possibility of tightening the laws is being considered in the UK, New Zealand, South Africa and India.
Many smokers in Australia are demonstrating a defiance of innovation.
These pictures don't bother me.
I'm just not paying attention.
"You just take a cigarette out and put it in your pocket", explains Victor El Haig, a cigarette shopper with a picture of a mouth tumor on the pack.
Honestly, the only thing that could make me quit is my little girl.
James Yu, the manager of King of the Pack tobacco shop in Sydney's CBD, claims that the same packaging has made it difficult to arrange the products on the shelves
"It used to take me an hour to unload a new shipment, but now it takes me four hours", he laments.
"The government should have taken it and banned cigarettes altogether, we would have said, 'What are we going to do, it's over, we're closing the shop,'" he says, waving his hands.
Boredom in a world of electronic networks and fixed connections isn't so bad.
On that Thanksgiving, I had to spend five hours at the airport because our plane had a mechanical failure and was replaced by another plane, which we were waiting for.
So I had plenty of time to reflect on the nature of boredom.
I won't deceive you.
A half-day in an airport waiting for a flight is really boring, and books, magazines, iPhones, even duty-free stores, don't do much good.
However, more and more scientists and child- development experts are speaking out in favor of boredom.
They say that in certain situations it is not so bad for us and our children to be bored.
It forces the brain to divert to interesting, related topics, which may be conducive to creativity.
And in today's world, because we're all in front of screens all the time, the benefits of boredom pass us by.
Maybe we should aim for boredom?
I know.
And at the same time, no.
We'll get back to that.
I used to think, as many others have, that boredom was an invention of the relatively recent times, when people had more free time.
Not so, says Peter Toui, professor of Greek and Roman history at the University of Calgary in Canada and author of Boredom: A Lively History, Yale University Press, 2011.
"In fact, boredom has a very long history", he says.
Latin inscriptions about boredom dating back to the first century C.E. have been found on walls in Pompeii.
But it leaves open the question of how we define boredom.
The problem, says John D. Eastwood, an adjunct professor at York University in Ontario, Canada, is that the understanding and vision of boredom has often changed.
After studying the research on this subject and asking a target group of 100 people, Professor Eastwood and his colleagues came to the following definition: Boredom is when people "want but are unable to do something that would bring them satisfaction".
The difference between boredom and apathy, he says, is that a bored person does not do what he would like to do.
Apathy is the state of doing nothing.
The key to boredom, he says, is "attention deficit and the associated mood decline and the feeling that time is passing slowly".
Boredom can be described as being very similar to depression.
But Professor Eastwood argues that despite the possible connection between these conditions, bored people see the causes of problems in the world and in circumstances, while depressed people see problems in themselves.
Sometimes we think we're bored when we're really just having trouble focusing.
In their study, "The Untrained Mind: Defining Boredom in terms of Attention", published in the September issue of Perspectives on Psychological Science, Professor Eastwood and colleagues refer to a previous experiment in which participants listened to a tape recording of a person reading a journal.
Some participants also heard the loud sounds of an unrelated television program in a nearby room, others heard the same sounds at a low volume so that they could hardly be heard, and a third group listened only to a voice recording without a separate audio track.
The participants who heard the TV at a low volume reported that they were bored more often than others -- they had difficulty concentrating, but they didn't know why, and attributed it to boredom.
When we try to focus on a difficult or exciting task, interrupted attention can be boring, says Mark J. Fenske, an associate professor of neurology at the University of Guelph in Ontario and one of the authors of the study.
On the other hand, when we are doing something uninteresting, "such as looking at the flow of goods on the assembly line in search of a marriage, distracting music can help to escape boredom".
It was thought, he continues, that when people started to roll around in a chair or doodle on a piece of paper, they did it out of boredom, but we now know that it was actually just a way to physically keep them from relaxing.
"Research has shown that children who are allowed to twirl and turn around learn better and retain more information than children who are required to sit still", says Professor Fenske.
We all get bored at some point: a delayed flight, as I did, a monotonous speech, a boring movie.
However, different people exhibit different degrees of boredom.
In the 1980's, researchers developed a "boredom scale" to measure such individual traits.
The scale uses questions and statements to assess the performance of a person, such as "Many of my tasks are dull and monotonous" or "I am too busy to do anything".
Using such questionnaires, researchers found that boys are more likely to be bored than girls, says Steven Vodanovich, a professor of psychology at the University of West Florida, especially when there are a variety of external stimuli.
But in general, teenagers are often bored.
In 1991, Reed Larson, a professor of personal and social development at the University of Illinois, conducted an experiment in which he paged nearly 400 teenagers and their parents seven to eight times a day.
And he got the following results: 32% of teens said they were bored at school and during homework, and 23% said they were bored outside of school.
Yet, only 3 percent of parents said they were bored.
Professor Larson notes that he has no data on what similar data on boredom would be like now, 21 years later.
However, he knows that "the teenage years are the peak of boredom", mainly because children and teenagers are not allowed to have full control over what they do.
So back to my original question: Is boredom good for you?
Sometimes it doesn't, because in extreme cases, research shows, it can push people into absurd and dangerous physical activities, risky gambling, or substance abuse in an attempt to escape boredom.
On the other hand, many philosophers and writers have pondered the connection between boredom and creativity, says Professor Vodanovic, who has spent more than two decades studying the problem.
"That's how our brain tells us to do something else; that's what boredom is", says Gary Marcus, a professor of psychology at New York University.
However, that same brain does not always know what to do.
If you get bored and you direct that energy to playing guitar or cooking experiments, you'll do yourself a better job.
However, if you watch television, you will feel better for a while, and soon it will pass.
So if your child is bored and you give him an iPad, he will stop being bored, but he will not learn to deal with boredom on his own or manage his time and activity in any other way", says Professor Fenske.
"And these self-regulating skills are used in a wide variety of situations", he says.
Your child is learning not only to do things for himself, but also to have self-control in general.
I don't think boredom needs to be glorified.
But it's not a bad thing either.
Rather, you should learn to be comfortable with the non-stop flow of activity and technology.
Professor Eastwood agrees with that.
"We see it as a need to get bored more often, when boredom is an extremely unpleasant, insatiable desire to do something meaningful", he says.
In fact, people are looking for a way to get away from the stress of life and just relax.
"In today's world", he says, "we are used to constantly over-stimulating our senses, and when the silence comes, we are lost and don't know what to do".
