I didn't know that the faculty not only looked the other way when they were harassing conservative students, but they were also very much a part of it.
Political issues - the miners' strike, privatization and the government's refusal to impose sanctions against the apartheid government in South Africa - permeated the wooden-paneled walls of the auditoriums.
For my first seminar, I had to translate an 18th-century French text into English, and I wasn't prepared for what came next.
"Miss Wyatt", said the teacher, the late Harry Pitt, "please translate the first paragraph".
I had a hard time with the lyrics, and I got stuck.
Harry Pitt was a very gallant man with a face like a cake.
"Do the Thatcherites have no intention of learning French, or are they just lacking in brains?" he asked.
The other students were giggling.
I had tears in my eyes.
"I would advise you to take a few introductory French lessons in your spare time, unless you are very busy going about in society", Pitt said.
I went back to my room feeling very unhappy.
That evening at college, I was sitting alone at lunch; then someone tapped me on the shoulder.
