"Valentino prefers elegance to fame"
On the "Valentino: the master of sewing" exhibition that opened this week in London, ABC is speaking with Naty Abascal, Fiona Tissen-Bornemica and other prominent clients of the Italian designer
Somerset House, the former residence of England's Queen Elizabeth I, is the only place in the British capital to host an exhibition on Valentino Garavani.
The designer acknowledged this during the opening of "Valentino: the master of sewing", a triumphant retrospective exhibition that brings together more than 130 high-fashion dresses created by his "house" over the past 50 years.
"I love this palace", he says in his distinctive Italian accent.
This exhibition is the final part of a story whose only character is "il signor" Garavani, but it could not have been written without his celebrated clientele.
Valentino has always felt fascinated by the rare and distant world of the aristocracy.
The first hall of this exhibition, open until March 3, is full of personal letters and photographs signed by the most distinguished aristocrats, from Princess Salima Aga-Khan to Lord Snowdon, including Marie-Chantal, Princess of Greece, and Margaret, Princess of Great Britain.
Valentino shows these personal memories as the trophies of his social rise: from a humble tailor from the northern Italian town of Voghera to the idol of an international "elite".
There's nothing wrong with being in love with a royal court.
"At least they don't blow their cigarettes out on your gorgeous carpet, as some beautiful pop stars do", says Baroness Fiona Thyssen-Bornemisza.
In the '60s and '70s, we both lived in the Alps and were good friends.
Valentino is a master of no equal, and he welcomes his guests with generosity and elegance.
"We all loved coming to his chalet in Gstaad", explains ex-wife "Heiney" Thiessen, a close friend of forgotten beauties like Marella Anelli or Eugenie Niarchos.
Valentino always preferred elegance to glory.
And yet, he is a star.
Valeria Mazza, who represents Valentino
Argentine model Valeria Mazza is remembered as a charismatic fashion designer.
We went to his house for dinner once, after a fashion show in Piazza di Spagna in Rome, many years ago.
Among the 20 invited were Sharon Stone and John F. Kennedy, Jr.
Valentino's style was in everything - in every detail of his apartment, in its decor, in the food, in the music.
