The hardest job in the world: the miners of Kawah-Ijen
Indonesian miners risk their lives and health to haul 70 kilograms of sulfur up the steep rocky trails to the top of a volcano for four euros
There are people who think their jobs are hell, and there are people who literally work in hell.
Among them is Antho Vijaya, one of 400 miners who earn their living by mining sulfur from the Kawah Ijen volcano on the eastern Indonesian island of Java.
Every day, Antho descends to the bottom of the crater, where sulfuric gas rises from the depths of the Earth, freezing upon contact with air.
He carves out huge pieces of sulfur, weighing up to 70 kilograms, and he lays them in two bamboo baskets, puts the baskets on his shoulders, and carries them up the steep, rocky road.
The summit of the 2,386-meter-high volcano is only 250 meters, but it takes the exhausted truckers more than 40 minutes to climb with a tortoise-like stride, struggling to maintain balance and carefully tapping the road to avoid slipping and falling off the cliff.
They know that one wrong step could cost them their lives, as happened to a French tourist who fell off the cliffs of Cave-Ijean a few years ago.
The miners of Kawah Ijen earn 5 eurocents for every kilogram of sulphur they extract
Once on top, they make their way among the tourists, who take photographs of them as if they were circus monkeys, and, tired of carrying heavy baskets, they walk three kilometers to the scales that the mining company has placed just above, at an altitude of 6,200 feet [1,850 m].
We are talking about PT Kandi Ngrimbi, a company that has been operating this volcano since 1960, and, better not to mention, its employees, to whom it pays 662 Indonesian Rupees (5 Euro cents) for each kilogram of sulfur.
It then sells it for 10,000 rupees (83 euro cents) to petrochemical industries, as this mineral is common in everyday life and is used to make matches, fireworks, cosmetics, dynamite and even sugar bleaching.
"Because the norm is a 70-kilogram load, we earn about 46,000 rupees (£3.50) for each load", explains Antô, who usually does three daily loads.
He spends three hours on each of them and feels crushed at the end, but they allow him to accumulate 138,000 rupees (US$40.00) by the end of the day.
While it may seem a pittance for such an inhuman endeavor, it's three times what he would have earned in the field.
"The daily wage for miners is very high by local standards, where the coffee harvest is 15,000 rupees (1.2 euros) a day and the average monthly wage is two million rupees (167 euros)", explains a shipper who used to work as a stonemason on the tourist island of Bali.
His salary there was 75,000 rupees a day and the site was not that hard, but Antho returned with his family to Banyuwangi, a town near the volcano, for a good reason, which in Indonesia is as devastating as sulfur: "I married a girl from Bali, where she was a Hindu, and brought her to Java to convert to Islam".
Anto has asthma, he breathes with difficulty, he coughs constantly, and his eyes are watering from toxic gases.
At 27, Anto spent three years risking his life in Kawah-ijen, whose sulfur had already begun to affect him despite the presence of a mask and special glasses.
He has asthma, he's breathing hard, he's coughing all the time, and he's got tears in his eyes from the toxic gases that the volcano is releasing.
It's the price he has to pay for his dream.
"I'm going to work for two more years because I want to open a shop or learn Spanish or French", he promises in more than acceptable English.
Punished by life, this nice and smart young man could be a tour guide, a waiter or a hotel porter, but instead he's doing the work of a mule.
To share his filthy wooden hut with other porters, he gets up at two o'clock every morning, because the sulfur never stops flowing at night, when its characteristic yellow color turns blue and sparkles in the darkness.
Defying the shadows, Antô descends into the crater, illuminating his way with a small lantern attached to his helmet, which he bought with his own money.
About 400 porters carry baskets of sulfur on their shoulders from the bottom of the volcano
Despite the high profits, the mining company has not mechanized sulfur extraction to save costs and does not provide any equipment to the carriers, who work for their own account and with such deprivation.
In fact, they don't even get a fraction of the 30,000 rupee (2.5 euros) photo-taking fee that, along with the 15,000 rupee (1.2 euros) admission ticket, the park guards charge tourists who come to take pictures of the volcano and its mule people.
"This job is for cattle, not for people", says Badrusin, a 42-year-old corn-fed porter who has spent three decades at Kawah-Ijen since leaving college.
Able to lift up to 110 kilos, he says he will work "as long as he can" because he needs money for the education of his three children, ages 18 to 10.
I'm not retiring, I'm dying here because the volcano is my life.
Although the sulphur burns their throats and eyes when the wind suddenly changes and traps the miners in thick pillars of smoke rising from the volcano, they are so enduring that none of them complain of their severe illnesses... more serious, obviously, than their usual breathing problems, arthritis, knee pain, and ulcers on the shoulders that have deformed under the weight of the baskets.
Balancing the basket on his back, Unaynik can now lift only 50 kilograms at the age of 53.
Each day, he and his companions haul 15 tons of sulfur from the volcano, which three trucks carry to a warehouse in Tamanusari, over a narrow, 18 kilometer [18 km] trail through the thick brush.
"I will not retire, I will die here, because the volcano is my whole life", declares Unaiknik, opening his mouth wide, which is missing several teeth.
Of his five children, the oldest, 30, also works as a sulfur courier.
Time passes, but poverty perpetuates one of the most difficult jobs in the world, the work of the human mules of Kawah-Ejen, from generation to generation.
Singapore is looking for babies to save the economy
Singaporeans blame career, stress, and the cost of housing and education for the lack of children.
"Singapore's population needs to grow".
I'm a patriot husband, you're my patriot wife, we do our civic duty and create life!
It may seem incredible that these lines are part of a peppermint ad, but despite this -- or perhaps because of this -- this video became a YouTube hit in Singapore earlier this year.
These phrases are part of a rap that uses local sayings such as "Let's put bao in the stove" to make fun of the birth rate in Singapore.
The advertising agency that made the video, BBH, hopes to use the ads to bring attention to the problem in an entertaining way.
Its creative director, Douglas Hamilton, says he wanted to use the power of music to get people to fulfill "their national duty".
This thing is exclusively for the Internet, so we had to make it fun and funny.
It's the biggest problem in the country.
We're the worst in the world at reproducing our own kind, so we felt like this was a topic we had to address.
We knew that the government was trying to do a lot of things, like launch pheromone sprays or have bliss parties.
Many of these ideas may have been creative, but they didn't necessarily work.
So we thought, why don't we do the most creative thing we can do to solve this problem, which is to write a rap?
1.2 of the child
Whoever doesn't take this lightly is the Singapore government.
It spends $1,300 a year on policies to encourage citizens to have more children.
The government's package for couples and parents provides up to $15,000 per child, extended maternity leave and tax breaks.
But all of this is low-efficiency.
Singapore is a wealthy and high-tech city-state in Southeast Asia, also known for its conservative leadership and its strict public controls.
The birth rate in Singapore, according to its national population administration, is currently 1.2 children per woman.
The last time it was below 2 - what's known as the replacement rate - was in 1976.
So why don't Singaporeans have more children?
Tan Wei Ming, director of the Marriage and Family Policy Unit of the National Population Administration, says that the reason is "improved education" and "a wider range of career opportunities".
"It has allowed people to have a wider range of options in terms of life goals and priorities beyond getting married and starting a family", she explains.
These changes in social norms have contributed to the rise in singleness and the delay in marriage and childbearing, resulting in a declining birth rate in Singapore.
Meanwhile, the immigration policy, which aims to dramatically increase immigration to counter the decline in population, is causing outrage among the local population.
There are websites in Singapore that are flourishing with a thinly veiled xenophobia towards many new immigrants, especially Chinese, who are criticized for keeping wages low and not wanting to integrate.
The rise in immigration is also seen as one of the reasons why Singapore's ruling party last year scored its worst result in an election since independence.
After the election, there was an attempt to solve the problem by using quotas and higher taxes for foreign workers.
Unexpected Consequences
While the falling birth rate has some impact on a nation's economic growth, tax revenues, health care spending and immigration policy, Singapore's example is also starting to have some unexpected consequences.
The government is working to reduce the number of tiny homes.
For example, it's starting to affect the real estate sector.
The city development authority has moved to control the number of small apartments, known as "shoe boxes", that can be built in certain areas of the city.
These apartments, 46 square meters, are selling very well.
However, there is a perception that they may promote a single-family lifestyle and deprive developers of the incentive to build large family homes.
