They're more popular, in the sense that they sell out for days, weeks, faster than the larger apartments.
As a result, our income increases.
However, he acknowledges that the new regulations provide clearer guidelines for developers who have previously been put on the back burner if they wanted to offer too many small apartments in a project.
Too much pressure.
Singapore is a city-state.
While these new rules may be a step towards increasing the national birth rate, after talking to Singaporeans who work in the financial district of the city centre, it seems that they will not have much effect.
"People are very stressed, housing is expensive, education is expensive, and that's why a lot of people put it off", says a young manager.
Other people can have children.
"But it's important for me to have my own money and my own time", says another young man in his 20's.
Men and women cite their careers, stress, and the cost of housing and education as reasons that prevent them from having children.
So no matter how hard the government tries to encourage its citizens to have children, when it comes to childbearing, the ultimate decision is left to the Singaporeans.
Offline personal is online personal
Confidentiality is important.
According to the Royal Spanish Academy's dictionary, it is a property of the private or "the sphere of private life that has the right to be protected from any interference".
What is personal to a minor under 16?
How does he apply this definition in his daily life and in social media?
Does he understand the dangers of discussing things online that he would not likely discuss otherwise?
ElPeriódico interviewed five youngsters between the ages of 10 and 15 who are frequent users of the network.
In four cases, they associated the term with "something very mine", in the personal realm, and "password and username", when applied to social networks.
"I wouldn't post my biggest secrets", says Jorge, 10, as he tries to explain the meaning of being private on sites like Facebook, Twitter, Hotmail and Windows Live Messenger, where he has had accounts for two years.
"These are very secret secrets, my mother may know them, but not the whole world", he claims.
I upload beautiful pictures or pictures from games to FB.
I also have fun with my friends.
"I wouldn't share a picture that wasn't mine or someone who was being silly", he says.
The boy realizes that it is wrong to post indecent pictures of naked people, crimes, or to write offensive or angry comments.
Jorge claims to know the 35 friends he has on FB and the nine people he follows on Twitter.
Most of them are relatives.
Mother knows, she has the password to one of the accounts.
I started Twitter to express myself and to write interesting tweets.
"I don't know if they're responding to me, I'm just uploading them", he adds.
"Social media is fun, and I can talk to distant relatives or friends in a quick way", he says.
Without hesitation, he replies that he would never accept a request from a stranger.
Wouldn't count on someone recommending him to a stranger.
The case of 14-year-old José is different.
This teenager has open accounts on Hotmail, Facebook, My Space and Ask, and in the last one admits not knowing 20 people added to his friends list.
"It doesn't scare me because we have something in common, like music", he points out.
According to the boy, no one approached him in confidence and asked for his home address or phone number.
"If I am pressured or asked to do something, I will simply delete them from my account", he admits.
Jose became an Ask follower after reading a Twitter recommendation.
The boy is no stranger to what is now known as cyberbullying.
A friend of mine was blackmailed on social media.
He was threatened and extorted money.
"He never knew who it was", he says.
The victim, according to Jose, never deleted the account.
"I just turned on privacy".
He then explains the sequence of steps to set up the account in a secure way.
Unlike Jorge, this boy would upload photos of people he knew in awkward or confusing situations.
Yeah, I would if I didn't like the person or if I wanted to.
"Although I know it's cyberbullying", he confirms.
Key issues
Marylos Porras, an English teacher and an expert in education and training, believes that in order to guide children and adolescents, it is important to understand that the purpose of social networks is to inform.
"The Internet was created as a way to find information, but the rules of the game have changed with the advent of these sites", she says.
Porras points out that academician Mark Prensky, a master's in education from Yale University and author of Digital Aborigines and Immigrants, coined these terms to explain the phenomenon.
Digital Aborigines are those children and youth who were born in the age of technology.
"We are digital immigrants who have to teach them while we are still learning ourselves", she says.
She explains that the issue is complicated "because we ask them to have a certain criteria for what they can and cannot share, publish or say, at an age when they are not mature enough to do so".
"They also have to be selective, whereas the most important thing for them is to be popular, to have thousands of friends, without thinking about the consequences", she adds.
The most effective way to teach children and adolescents about privacy is to ask thought-provoking questions, says the expert.
"Telling them not to do it is useless", she adds.
Porras then lists some options: there are things you wouldn't tell a stranger, so why are you doing it online?
Or would you like to have a picture of you posted, like the one you posted of your friend?
Do you know what others are posting about you?
When you sign party photos, do you ask other people's permission to mark them?
And one more thing, does everyone need to know what you're doing at any given moment?
Another point is to make them understand that they should behave online the same way they behave offline.
The rules are the same.
"Outside the Internet, people behave with respect, responsibility and other principles, and so should social media", she says.
Watching
Estuardo Guardia, a university lecturer, elementary school teacher and educational consultant, explains the need for family heads to read social media policies in good faith.
Understanding each of these points will give parents a good basis for discussing with their children the requirements for opening an Internet account.
"For example, age and what you're allowed to share or post", he says.
According to Gaurdia, the key is to remind children of the lesson "don't talk to strangers".
UNASUR summit ends without the publication of the Lime Declaration
The 6th Summit of the Union of South American Nations (UNASUR) ended today in Peru without the promulgation of the Lima Declaration, which was announced earlier and theoretically signed by seven mandatory participants.
Efe has repeatedly tried to access the document signed at the VI UNASUR meeting of heads of state and government, but sources from the Office and the Presidential Administration indicated on the homepage that it would be delivered after closing, but then confirmed that at a certain point it would be published on the website of the Peruvian government.
When asked about the text, they indicated that the content was laid out by Peru's President, Ollanta Humala, during brief statements to the press.
Access to information about the Summit has been limited at all times.
During the day, a video of the presidential assembly was broadcast in the press room without sound with the message "the meeting is closed, the sound is prohibited".
Some of the information that was circulated among reporters was shared by the spokesmen of some of the UNASUR governments that were present at the meeting, but not the Peruvian one.
The only document distributed during the day was the list of participating presidents, which provoked the ire of hundreds of journalists from various national and international media outlets who asked for more information.
The Peruvian presidential administration subsequently sent an email to the media with the summit's "final declaration", but it was a statement by Umala, not the official document that ended the summit.
Last October, Peru hosted the Third Summit of South American and Arab Countries (ASPA), and this time, despite the press' insistence, the so-called Lim Declaration, which had been announced earlier, was not circulated.
You can check the ASAP website to see that the document was published last Tuesday.
At both international meetings, the Peruvian authorities tried to ensure that all journalists had access to the information, but restricted access to the information as much as possible.
The summit also concluded with Chile and Peru jointly adopting the Hague Court verdict that settles the territorial dispute between the two countries.
The presidents of Peru, Ollanta Humala, and Chile, Sebastián Piñera, gathered at the regional meeting and ratified that they will abide by the decision of the International Court of Justice, which will begin hearing both sides' statements on Monday in The Hague, as part of the indictment that Lima has brought against Santiago.
"We will respect and enforce the decision that will clarify the differences that we are presently presenting to this international court", said Umalla, standing next to his Chilean counterpart.
"Chile has been, is and will be a country that respects international law, peaceful resolution of disputes, pacts and international tribunals", added Pinera, and shook hands with Umalu against the background of the flags of the two countries.
The confirmation by both presidents that they will obey the International Court of Justice comes just after Colombia this week challenged the Bogotá Pact, which recognized its submission to the verdicts of this international court after the decision on the maritime boundaries with Nicaragua, which it considered erroneous.
The summit was held in the absence of the presidents of Brazil, Dilma Rousseff; Venezuela, Hugo Chavez; Bolivia, Evo Morales; and Argentina, Cristina Kirchner.
Paraguay, whose membership in UNASUR has been suspended since 2011 following the impeachment of its former president Fernando Lugo, did not participate in the meeting.
The host president, Olly M. Umal, was responsible for opening the discussions in the morning and closing the summit, just after noon on Lima time.
The head of state read the final document, in which he reported that 16 agreements were accepted and approved directions of action for 31 projects among South American countries, the amount of the expected investments amounted to 17 billion dollars.
Among the agreements he mentioned, UNASUR countries will take "important steps towards the goal of South American citizenship, for which we are expanding the agreements on residency".
He reported that actions are being taken to improve "cooperation in the fight against insecurity and against transnational organized crime, actions to increase the availability of medicines, low-cost Internet access in all parts of South America and to take into account the risks of natural disasters in a collective and effective way".
Since Europe is in crisis, "economic integration (of Latin America) should not have a triumphal basis, but should serve to expand our manufacturing base and envision a better future for our cities", added Umala.
"We have decided to privilege a group of 31 landmark projects that will improve the connectivity of South America, especially in rural and border areas... uniting our countries and forming new economic schemes", the Peruvian president said in a statement read out.
Among these projects, he mentioned that five are related to Peru, and are limited to the transverse axes in its territory, from the coast to Brazil, and two are aimed at a greater connection with Ecuador, but he did not provide more details.
The final document also touched on the political situation in Paraguay.
"We hope that the electoral process in this country will serve to re-join the Union of South American Nations", from which it is currently excluded.
The need for Latin America to remain a region of prosperity and peace, united, and with good relations between neighbors was another theme emphasized at the summit.
In this sense, the Colombian President, Juan Manuel Santos, said before he started to participate in the regional meeting that he hoped to meet his Nicaraguan counterpart, Daniel Ortega, on Saturday in Mexico City to negotiate in a respectful manner the maritime dispute resulting from the verdict of the international court challenged by Bogotá.
"The day after tomorrow (Saturday), I may meet with President Daniel Ortega", Santos said.
"We will review all these paths, they are not mutually exclusive, including the pact with Nicaragua will require discussion with Nicaragua", he stressed.
"With President Ortega, I hope I can tell him that we will deal with this in the most civilized and respectful way possible", Santos added.
Santos and Ortega will meet on Saturday in Mexico City, where they are scheduled to attend the inauguration of the country's new president, Enrique Peña Nieto.
Also at the summit, the bloc's defence ministers met in advance to approve the 2013 Action Plan, which aims to strengthen dialogue and consensus on the region's defence.
Argentina, Bolivia, Colombia, Ecuador, Peru, Brazil, Uruguay, Venezuela, Chile, Guyana, Suriname and Paraguay form UNASUR, although the participation of the latter country has been suspended.
Peru has the provisional presidency of the regional bloc.
