AIDS deaths today are the result of late diagnosis
Fabrizio was 21 when it was announced that he had tested positive for AIDS.
"I felt as if I had been stunned", he recalls, "despite the doctor's tact, it was a difficult moment".
The young man hid it from his family.
Deciding to fight the disease on his own, he wanted to learn as much as he could about it, and his efforts paid off - he had already celebrated his 43rd birthday.
Fabrizio is one of the "oldest" HIV patients in the Hospital Civil de Guadalajara (HCG), where he arrived in 1994 after overcoming many obstacles.
He has lived with the human immunodeficiency virus (HIV) for 22 years, and in the early 1990s, it would have been difficult to believe that - there were too few treatment options, too little knowledge about the disease, too much prejudice against the sick.
For example, even the director of the clinic at the Mexican Institute of Social Protection refused to say goodbye to him "because he had a cut".
In other words, in those days, having AIDS was a judgment call.
It's now possible to survive with this syndrome and do it without a deterioration in quality of life.
Yet, many people still come in unaware of their illness when the virus has already damaged, "squeezed" their immune system, and they suffer from opportunistic infections.
Thirty-one years after the emergence of AIDS in the world, at least since the first reported cases, "the big achievement at this point is that the survival of a patient who starts treatment on time and the survival of the general population are exactly the same", said the head of the HCG's HIV department, Jaime Andrade Vilyanueva, citing the fact that this information was confirmed in April this year in a prestigious scientific publication.
Infectionist and HIV/AIDS expert Andrade Villanueva explained that since 2008 scientists have concluded that AIDS is not a sentence, but that life expectancy and quality of life depend on the degree of damage to the immune system that patients have at the time of diagnosis, with the best life expectancy in those who do not use drugs: up to 30 years with a CD4 count of 200 and up to 50 years when a CD4 count of 500 is reported.
Simply put, this means that a person diagnosed as HIV-positive at age 25 would, in these terms, "live to age 75 with no problems", he explained.
To appreciate this progress, it is worth remembering that the average life expectancy of Mexicans today is 76 years.
While the death rate has decreased significantly in recent years, in the case of Mexico, the number of people dying from AIDS decreased from 6,678 in 2007 to 4,862 in 2011 (UNEIDS annual report), it is also true that since the emergence of AIDS, 60 percent of the patients in the national database have died.
In Jalisco alone, 255 people died in 2011, and 187 deaths had been reported by May of this year; however, it is claimed that there has been universal access to antiretroviral drugs since 2005.
- Why are there still fatalities?
- Personally, I don't think the problem is access to treatment.
That's how I see it, that's how it works in our hospital.
We haven't had a shortage of medicine for at least the last 12 years, the problem is that patients come in very late because they don't know they're infected, that is, in the late stages of the disease.
He cited the overwhelming data: "Nine out of ten patients come when they already have some opportunistic infection; what we need to do to have a greater impact on the overall mortality is to diagnose earlier, and therefore provide samples for mass detection to all the people who ask for it".
The proposal is shared by experts and officials of the State Council for the Prevention of AIDS in Jalisco (COESIDA), as well as by patients themselves, such as Fabrizio, who went to a private laboratory for testing, motivated only by the fact that a friend had done it, and despite his young age, he was already in the AIDS stage and even suffered from Kaposi's sarcoma, a cancerous tumor that is one of the common complications.
Everything changes when you know you have AIDS.
Some people think they're gonna die, and they don't want to know.
"If I'm going to die, I'd better be getting laid three times a week", they say.
I'm doing well, I'm eating well, I'm exercising, I'm taking some medication.
To this day, his parents only know that he has cancer.
I live a normal life like everyone else.
"I work, I have many activities, I travel, I have an active sex life, but with mutual responsibility, taking care of myself and the other person", said Fabrizio, who agreed to share his personal life with MILENIO JALISCO to encourage his statement to those who are now experiencing fear in the context of World AIDS Day.
Let them know if they're at risk of contracting HIV, let them know as soon as they know they're HIV positive, it's better, and if they're diagnosed, let them know they can live like everyone else, be responsible.
This message sums up the theme of the fight against AIDS in 2012.
Condoms on the counter.
The gap between health programs and the average citizen is wide, says Ricardo Salazar, a journalist from Guadalajara who has been covering the HIV problem.
And the biggest one is prevention.
In places dedicated to this task, "the distribution of condoms has actually increased, we used to be given one or two, now we are given packages of a hundred, and that's very good, but it turns out that there are those who still don't have access to condoms", he said.
Among the most vulnerable to new infections are teenagers.
"Why do you need them?" is a popular question, with echoes of condemnation from social workers, school counselors, pharmacists and health workers, that teenagers don't want to hear, the propagandist asserted.
I propose that we change this inefficient distribution, so that condoms are not just behind the counter, but that hundreds of them are in the vending machines in public toilets in places that young people frequent.
It's not an incentive for debauchery.
It's not about paying for beer and a motel, said Governor Emilio González when asked if it's possible to give out condoms under his administration.
"It's not sexuality, it's best to make condoms available to those who are already sexually active", he said.
Key facts about Jalisco
A total of 13,435 cases were recorded (12,158 AIDS and 1,317 HIV).
The state ranks 4th nationally in new and total AIDS cases and 13th in HIV.
92% of infections are sexually transmitted, 6% are bloodborne and 2% are perinatal.
It is estimated that 50,000 people may be living with HIV, since for every registered case, there are four to five people who do not know it.
